if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_neck']=[
  {q:"A 45-year-old man undergoes radical neck dissection for metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy. Postoperatively, he is unable to shrug his shoulder on the operated side. The injured nerve is:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Spinal accessory nerve","Phrenic nerve","Facial nerve"],a:2,e:"Spinal accessory nerve injury fits inability to shrug shoulder after neck dissection. Shoulder droop develops clinically due to trapezius paralysis.<br><br>The spinal accessory nerve traverses the posterior triangle superficially after supplying sternocleidomastoid, making it particularly vulnerable during cervical node surgery.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), phrenic nerve (option D), and facial nerve (option E) do not primarily innervate trapezius. Therefore spinal accessory nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The carotid sheath contains all EXCEPT:",o:["Internal jugular vein","Common carotid artery","Vagus nerve","Sympathetic chain","Internal carotid artery"],a:3,e:"Sympathetic chain does not lie within carotid sheath. Horner syndrome develops clinically when cervical sympathetic fibers are damaged.<br><br>The carotid sheath encloses major neurovascular structures extending from skull base to thoracic inlet, while the sympathetic trunk runs posteriorly outside it.<br><br>Internal jugular vein (option A), common carotid artery (option B), vagus nerve (option C), and internal carotid artery (option E) are true sheath contents. Therefore sympathetic chain is excluded.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops hoarseness following thyroidectomy. The most likely injured structure is:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Superior cervical ganglion","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Lingual nerve","Great auricular nerve"],a:2,e:"Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury fits postoperative hoarseness after thyroid surgery. Vocal cord paralysis develops clinically commonly.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within the tracheoesophageal groove close to inferior thyroid vessels, making it vulnerable during gland mobilization.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A), superior cervical ganglion (option B), lingual nerve (option D), and great auricular nerve (option E) are less directly related. Therefore recurrent laryngeal nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The posterior triangle of neck is bounded anteriorly by:",o:["Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Trapezius muscle","Platysma","Digastric muscle","Omohyoid muscle"],a:0,e:"Sternocleidomastoid muscle fits the anterior boundary of posterior triangle. Neck masses develop clinically within this anatomical region.<br><br>The posterior triangle is an important surgical landmark containing accessory nerve, cervical plexus branches, and supraclavicular lymph nodes.<br><br>Trapezius muscle (option B) forms posterior boundary; platysma (option C), digastric muscle (option D), and omohyoid muscle (option E) do not define the anterior border. Therefore sternocleidomastoid is correct.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A swelling moving upward on protrusion of tongue is most likely:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Lipoma","Cystic hygroma"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cyst fits a midline neck swelling moving with tongue protrusion. Infection develops clinically in recurrent cases.<br><br>Persistent attachment to the foramen cecum through remnants of thyroglossal tract explains characteristic movement during tongue movements and swallowing.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option C), lipoma (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) usually do not move this way. Therefore thyroglossal cyst is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The common carotid artery bifurcates at the level of:",o:["C2 vertebra","C4 vertebra","C6 vertebra","T1 vertebra","Hyoid tip only"],a:1,e:"C4 vertebral level fits bifurcation of common carotid artery into internal and external carotid branches. Carotid pulse develops clinically at this level.<br><br>The bifurcation typically lies near the upper border of thyroid cartilage where carotid sinus and carotid body are anatomically located.<br><br>C2 vertebra (option A), C6 vertebra (option C), T1 vertebra (option D), and isolated hyoid tip (option E) are inaccurate landmarks. Therefore C4 is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with penetrating neck injury develops diaphragmatic paralysis. The injured nerve is likely:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Phrenic nerve","Accessory nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:2,e:"Phrenic nerve injury fits diaphragmatic paralysis after neck trauma. Respiratory distress develops clinically with unilateral diaphragmatic elevation.<br><br>The phrenic nerve descends vertically across anterior scalene muscle before entering thorax, placing it at risk during deep cervical injuries.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), accessory nerve (option D), and lingual nerve (option E) do not innervate diaphragm. Therefore phrenic nerve is affected.<br><br><em>(Recall and Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important landmark dividing anterior and posterior triangles of neck is the:",o:["Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Digastric muscle","Platysma","Omohyoid tendon","Trapezius muscle"],a:0,e:"Sternocleidomastoid muscle fits the major landmark dividing neck triangles. Cervical swellings develop clinically relative to this structure.<br><br>Its oblique course from mastoid process to sternum and clavicle separates anterior visceral compartments from posterior neurovascular regions.<br><br>Digastric muscle (option B), platysma (option C), omohyoid tendon (option D), and trapezius muscle (option E) are less central landmarks. Therefore sternocleidomastoid is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A lateral neck cyst anterior to sternocleidomastoid in a young adult is most likely:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst","Ranula","Sebaceous cyst"],a:0,e:"Branchial cyst fits a painless lateral neck swelling in young adults. Secondary infection develops clinically after upper respiratory infections.<br><br>These cysts arise from remnants of branchial apparatus, usually along the anterior border of sternocleidomastoid near upper jugular chain.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option C), ranula (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) have different locations. Therefore branchial cyst is likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The external jugular vein pierces which fascia before draining into subclavian vein?",o:["Prevertebral fascia","Investing layer of deep cervical fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia","Carotid sheath","Pretracheal fascia"],a:1,e:"Investing layer of deep cervical fascia fits the structure pierced by external jugular vein. Venous air embolism develops clinically if injured.<br><br>The external jugular vein courses superficially across sternocleidomastoid before penetrating deep fascia just above clavicle to enter subclavian vein.<br><br>Prevertebral fascia (option A), buccopharyngeal fascia (option C), carotid sheath (option D), and pretracheal fascia (option E) are unrelated. Therefore investing fascia is correct.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with carotid body tumor presents with pulsatile neck swelling at carotid bifurcation. The carotid body functions primarily as a:",o:["Baroreceptor","Chemoreceptor","Mechanoreceptor","Thermoreceptor","Pain receptor"],a:1,e:"Chemoreceptor function fits carotid body physiology in monitoring blood oxygen and carbon dioxide levels. Reflex respiratory changes develop clinically accordingly.<br><br>The carotid body contains specialized glomus cells highly sensitive to hypoxia and participates in respiratory drive regulation.<br><br>Baroreceptor (option A), mechanoreceptor (option C), thermoreceptor (option D), and pain receptor (option E) describe different sensory modalities. Therefore carotid body is a chemoreceptor.<br><br><em>(Recall and Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops torticollis due to fibrosis of which muscle?",o:["Sternocleidomastoid","Platysma","Trapezius","Omohyoid","Digastric"],a:0,e:"Sternocleidomastoid fibrosis fits congenital muscular torticollis. Head tilt develops clinically toward affected side.<br><br>Shortening of this muscle rotates the chin away from lesion side while limiting normal neck movements in infants and children.<br><br>Platysma (option B), trapezius (option C), omohyoid (option D), and digastric muscle (option E) are less commonly implicated. Therefore sternocleidomastoid is responsible.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The ansa cervicalis supplies:",o:["Muscles of mastication","Infrahyoid muscles","Tongue muscles","Facial muscles","Extraocular muscles"],a:1,e:"Ansa cervicalis fits motor supply of infrahyoid strap muscles. Swallowing coordination develops clinically through these muscles.<br><br>This cervical nerve loop originates from upper cervical spinal roots and innervates sternohyoid, sternothyroid, and omohyoid muscles.<br><br>Muscles of mastication (option A), tongue muscles (option C), facial muscles (option D), and extraocular muscles (option E) receive different innervation. Therefore infrahyoid muscles are supplied.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic cervical nodes develops Horner syndrome. The affected structure is likely the:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain","Lingual nerve","Facial artery","External jugular vein"],a:1,e:"Cervical sympathetic chain involvement fits Horner syndrome with ptosis and miosis. Anhidrosis develops clinically on affected side.<br><br>Sympathetic fibers ascend along cervical chain close to deep neck nodes, making them vulnerable to malignant infiltration or surgical injury.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option C), facial artery (option D), and external jugular vein (option E) do not produce Horner syndrome. Therefore sympathetic chain is involved.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The carotid sinus primarily functions as a:",o:["Baroreceptor","Chemoreceptor","Thermoreceptor","Nociceptor","Osmoreceptor"],a:0,e:"Baroreceptor function fits carotid sinus physiology in blood pressure regulation. Reflex bradycardia develops clinically after stimulation.<br><br>Stretch-sensitive receptors within the dilated carotid sinus wall transmit afferent impulses through glossopharyngeal nerve to cardiovascular centers.<br><br>Chemoreceptor (option B), thermoreceptor (option C), nociceptor (option D), and osmoreceptor (option E) perform different sensory roles. Therefore carotid sinus is a baroreceptor.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops severe dysphagia and airway compromise. The most dangerous potential spread is into the:",o:["Mediastinum","Submandibular space only","Orbit","Parotid gland","Maxillary sinus"],a:0,e:"Mediastinal spread fits a dangerous complication of deep neck infections. Septic shock develops clinically if infection descends rapidly.<br><br>Deep cervical fascial planes communicate directly with superior mediastinum, allowing pus to track inferiorly along retropharyngeal and danger spaces.<br><br>Submandibular space only (option B), orbit (option C), parotid gland (option D), and maxillary sinus (option E) are less life-threatening pathways. Therefore mediastinal extension is feared.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The nerve closely related to apex of posterior triangle and vulnerable during subclavian vein cannulation is:",o:["Facial nerve","Phrenic nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Chorda tympani","Greater auricular nerve"],a:1,e:"Phrenic nerve injury fits diaphragmatic complications following central venous access near root of neck. Dyspnea develops clinically afterward.<br><br>The phrenic nerve descends over anterior scalene muscle close to subclavian vessels and pleural dome, creating procedural vulnerability.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option C), chorda tympani (option D), and greater auricular nerve (option E) lie elsewhere. Therefore phrenic nerve is at risk.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A neck swelling that increases on Valsalva maneuver is most likely vascular in origin because of relation with:",o:["Venous pressure changes","Intracranial pressure changes","Salivary secretion","Lymphatic obstruction only","Arterial vasospasm"],a:0,e:"Venous pressure changes fit neck swellings enlarging during Valsalva maneuver. Distension develops clinically in venous malformations.<br><br>Raised intrathoracic pressure impedes venous return temporarily, causing expansion of compliant cervical venous structures and vascular lesions.<br><br>Intracranial pressure changes (option B), salivary secretion (option C), lymphatic obstruction only (option D), and arterial vasospasm (option E) are less likely explanations. Therefore venous pressure is responsible.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The deep cervical fascia layer enclosing trapezius and sternocleidomastoid is the:",o:["Investing fascia","Prevertebral fascia","Pretracheal fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia","Alar fascia"],a:0,e:"Investing fascia fits the deep cervical fascial layer surrounding sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles. Surgical planes develop clinically along this layer.<br><br>This superficial layer of deep fascia encircles the neck like a collar and contributes to parotid and submandibular gland capsules.<br><br>Pretracheal fascia (option C), prevertebral fascia (option B), buccopharyngeal fascia (option D), and alar fascia (option E) cover deeper compartments. Therefore investing fascia is correct.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroid malignancy develops fixed cervical nodes along internal jugular vein. These nodes belong to:",o:["Deep cervical chain","Posterior auricular chain","Submental group","Occipital group","Preauricular chain"],a:0,e:"Deep cervical chain involvement fits metastatic spread from thyroid malignancy. Neck swelling develops clinically along internal jugular course.<br><br>These lymph nodes accompany the jugular vein beneath sternocleidomastoid and drain major structures of head and neck.<br><br>Posterior auricular chain (option B), submental group (option C), occipital group (option D), and preauricular chain (option E) drain different territories. Therefore deep cervical chain is involved.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 52-year-old man undergoes total thyroidectomy. Postoperatively he develops stridor and bilateral immobile vocal cords on laryngoscopy. The most likely injured structure is:",o:["Superior laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerves","Hypoglossal nerves","Glossopharyngeal nerves","Cervical sympathetic chain"],a:1,e:"Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury fits postoperative stridor with bilateral vocal cord paralysis after thyroid surgery. Respiratory distress develops clinically urgently.<br><br>Both recurrent laryngeal nerves supply nearly all intrinsic laryngeal muscles responsible for vocal cord abduction and airway patency.<br><br>Superior laryngeal nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerves (option C), glossopharyngeal nerves (option D), and cervical sympathetic chain (option E) do not cause bilateral fixed cords. Therefore recurrent nerves are injured.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with painless cystic swelling along anterior border of sternocleidomastoid. The diagnosis is most likely:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma","Lipoma"],a:1,e:"Branchial cyst fits a lateral cystic neck swelling near sternocleidomastoid border. Infection develops clinically after recurrent upper respiratory tract infections.<br><br>These lesions originate from persistent remnants of branchial apparatus, usually related to second branchial cleft structures.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option C), cystic hygroma (option D), and lipoma (option E) show different locations and behavior. Therefore branchial cyst is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"During radical neck dissection, preservation of which structure is most important to prevent shoulder dysfunction?",o:["Lingual nerve","Phrenic nerve","Spinal accessory nerve","Marginal mandibular nerve","Facial artery"],a:2,e:"Spinal accessory nerve preservation fits prevention of postoperative shoulder weakness and trapezius wasting. Difficulty abducting shoulder develops clinically after injury.<br><br>The accessory nerve crosses posterior triangle superficially and remains especially vulnerable during cervical lymph node clearance procedures.<br><br>Lingual nerve (option A), phrenic nerve (option B), marginal mandibular nerve (option D), and facial artery (option E) are less directly responsible for shoulder function. Therefore accessory nerve is essential.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A midline neck swelling moving upward during swallowing and tongue protrusion is characteristic of:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Lipoma","Sebaceous cyst"],a:2,e:"Thyroglossal cyst fits a midline swelling moving with swallowing and tongue protrusion. Recurrent infection develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Embryologic persistence of thyroglossal tract maintains attachment to tongue base near foramen cecum, producing characteristic movement.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option A), branchial cyst (option B), lipoma (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) usually lack this mobility pattern. Therefore thyroglossal cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck abscess develops severe chest pain and mediastinitis. The infection most likely spread through:",o:["Carotid sheath","Danger space","Pretracheal fascia only","Submandibular space only","Buccal space"],a:1,e:"Danger space spread fits rapid extension of deep neck infections into mediastinum. Septic deterioration develops clinically aggressively.<br><br>The danger space lies between alar and prevertebral fascia and extends uninterrupted from skull base into posterior mediastinum.<br><br>Carotid sheath (option A), pretracheal fascia only (option C), submandibular space only (option D), and buccal space (option E) are less direct pathways. Therefore danger space is implicated.<br><br><em>(Recall and Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops tongue deviation to right side after carotid endarterectomy. Which nerve was most likely injured?",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Facial nerve","Vagus nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:1,e:"Hypoglossal nerve injury fits ipsilateral tongue deviation after carotid surgery. Dysarthria develops clinically with tongue weakness.<br><br>The hypoglossal nerve crosses carotid arteries high in neck and remains vulnerable during procedures near carotid bifurcation.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A), facial nerve (option C), vagus nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) do not directly control tongue protrusion. Therefore hypoglossal nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The ansa cervicalis is formed by cervical spinal roots:",o:["C1-C3","C4,C6","C2,C5","C5,T1","C1 only"],a:0,e:"C1-C3 roots fit formation of ansa cervicalis supplying strap muscles. Swallowing coordination develops clinically through these muscles.<br><br>Superior root fibers travel briefly with hypoglossal nerve before joining lower cervical contributions to form the nerve loop.<br><br>C4,C6 (option B), C2,C5 (option C), C5,T1 (option D), and isolated C1 (option E) are inaccurate combinations. Therefore C1-C3 are correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with pulsatile neck swelling that moves side-to-side but not vertically. The diagnosis is most suggestive of:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Carotid body tumor","Lipoma","Cystic hygroma"],a:2,e:"Carotid body tumor fits a pulsatile swelling mobile horizontally but fixed vertically. Bruit develops clinically over larger lesions.<br><br>The tumor arises at carotid bifurcation where attachment to arterial adventitia limits vertical movement while permitting lateral mobility.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), branchial cyst (option B), lipoma (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) are usually nonpulsatile. Therefore carotid body tumor is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"During central venous catheterization through internal jugular vein, accidental puncture of which nearby artery is most common?",o:["External carotid artery","Common carotid artery","Lingual artery","Facial artery","Vertebral artery"],a:1,e:"Common carotid artery puncture fits a recognized complication during internal jugular cannulation. Expanding hematoma develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>The internal jugular vein lies lateral to carotid artery within carotid sheath, making arterial puncture possible during difficult access.<br><br>External carotid artery (option A), lingual artery (option C), facial artery (option D), and vertebral artery (option E) are less commonly injured. Therefore common carotid artery is implicated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn presents with soft brilliantly transilluminant swelling in posterior triangle of neck. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Dermoid cyst","Sebaceous cyst"],a:2,e:"Cystic hygroma fits a transilluminant congenital swelling in posterior triangle. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>These lymphatic malformations consist of dilated endothelial-lined spaces filled with lymphatic fluid extending between tissue planes.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) are less transilluminant. Therefore cystic hygroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The carotid sinus receives afferent innervation mainly from:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve","Vagus nerve only","Hypoglossal nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:0,e:"Glossopharyngeal nerve fits afferent innervation of carotid sinus baroreceptors. Reflex bradycardia develops clinically after stimulation.<br><br>Hering's nerve, a branch of glossopharyngeal nerve, transmits blood pressure information to medullary cardiovascular centers.<br><br>Facial nerve (option B), vagus nerve only (option C), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) are less important pathways. Therefore glossopharyngeal nerve predominates.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina is at greatest immediate risk of:",o:["Hearing loss","Airway obstruction","Facial paralysis","Blindness","Epistaxis"],a:1,e:"Airway obstruction fits the most feared complication of Ludwig angina. Tongue elevation develops clinically from floor-of-mouth edema.<br><br>Rapid cellulitis involving submandibular and sublingual spaces pushes soft tissues posteriorly, threatening upper airway patency.<br><br>Hearing loss (option A), facial paralysis (option C), blindness (option D), and epistaxis (option E) are less immediate concerns. Therefore airway compromise is critical.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The cervical sympathetic chain lies posterior to:",o:["Carotid sheath","Sternocleidomastoid only","Platysma","Thyroid gland","Trachea"],a:0,e:"Cervical sympathetic chain lies posterior to carotid sheath. Horner syndrome develops clinically after sympathetic disruption.<br><br>The chain runs along prevertebral fascia near vertebral column, separated from carotid sheath contents by fascial planes.<br><br>Sternocleidomastoid only (option B), platysma (option C), thyroid gland (option D), and trachea (option E) are not precise relationships. Therefore carotid sheath is correct.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops inability to tense neck skin after superficial neck injury. Which muscle was most likely damaged?",o:["Omohyoid","Platysma","Digastric","Sternohyoid","Mylohyoid"],a:1,e:"Platysma damage fits inability to tense skin of neck. Cosmetic asymmetry develops clinically during facial expression.<br><br>This thin superficial muscle extends from lower face into upper chest and contributes to grimacing and neck skin tightening.<br><br>Omohyoid (option A), digastric (option C), sternohyoid (option D), and mylohyoid (option E) perform different functions. Therefore platysma is involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A surgeon identifies a nerve running superficially across sternocleidomastoid toward parotid gland while excising cervical lymph nodes. The nerve is most likely:",o:["Great auricular nerve","Lingual nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve"],a:0,e:"Great auricular nerve fits a superficial cervical sensory nerve crossing sternocleidomastoid toward parotid region. Ear numbness develops clinically after injury.<br><br>This branch of cervical plexus supplies skin over parotid area, angle of mandible, and lower auricle.<br><br>Lingual nerve (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option C), phrenic nerve (option D), and recurrent laryngeal nerve (option E) follow deeper courses. Therefore great auricular nerve is correct.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic thyroid carcinoma develops Horner syndrome and hoarseness simultaneously. Which anatomical region is most likely involved?",o:["Posterior triangle only","Carotid sheath region","Submental triangle","Submandibular space","Parotid fascia"],a:1,e:"Carotid sheath region involvement fits combined recurrent laryngeal and sympathetic chain compression. Ptosis and vocal changes develop clinically together.<br><br>Advanced thyroid malignancies may infiltrate deep cervical neurovascular compartments adjacent to tracheoesophageal groove and sympathetic pathways.<br><br>Posterior triangle only (option A), submental triangle (option C), submandibular space (option D), and parotid fascia (option E) less commonly explain both findings. Therefore carotid sheath region is implicated.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The floor of posterior triangle is formed mainly by:",o:["Prevertebral muscles","Buccinator muscle","Sternothyroid muscle","Platysma","Digastric muscle"],a:0,e:"Prevertebral muscles fit the floor of posterior triangle. Deep neck infections develop clinically relative to these fascial layers.<br><br>Splenius capitis, levator scapulae, and scalene muscles covered by prevertebral fascia contribute to the triangle's deep boundary.<br><br>Buccinator muscle (option B), sternothyroid muscle (option C), platysma (option D), and digastric muscle (option E) are unrelated structures. Therefore prevertebral muscles form the floor.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with penetrating neck trauma develops chylous fistula after surgery. Which structure was most likely injured?",o:["External jugular vein","Thoracic duct","Vertebral artery","Facial vein","Lingual artery"],a:1,e:"Thoracic duct injury fits postoperative chylous fistula in lower neck surgery. Milky drainage develops clinically after meals.<br><br>The thoracic duct arches laterally in left root of neck before entering venous circulation near jugulosubclavian junction.<br><br>External jugular vein (option A), vertebral artery (option C), facial vein (option D), and lingual artery (option E) do not carry chyle. Therefore thoracic duct is injured.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A neck swelling that moves upward during swallowing but not with tongue protrusion is most likely arising from:",o:["Thyroid gland","Thyroglossal tract","Branchial apparatus","Lymphatic channels","Sebaceous glands"],a:0,e:"Thyroid gland swellings fit movement with swallowing because of attachment to laryngeal framework. Tongue protrusion does not alter position clinically.<br><br>The pretracheal fascia anchors thyroid gland to trachea and larynx, causing upward movement during deglutition.<br><br>Thyroglossal tract (option B), branchial apparatus (option C), lymphatic channels (option D), and sebaceous glands (option E) behave differently. Therefore thyroid origin is likely.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep cervical abscess develops septic thrombophlebitis involving a major venous structure inside carotid sheath. The affected vein is:",o:["Internal jugular vein","External jugular vein","Facial vein","Anterior jugular vein","Retromandibular vein"],a:0,e:"Internal jugular vein involvement fits septic thrombophlebitis within carotid sheath. Neck tenderness develops clinically along sternocleidomastoid.<br><br>The internal jugular vein descends within carotid sheath beside carotid artery and vagus nerve, making it susceptible to deep cervical infection spread.<br><br>External jugular vein (option B), facial vein (option C), anterior jugular vein (option D), and retromandibular vein (option E) lie outside carotid sheath. Therefore internal jugular vein is affected.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old man with metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy undergoes modified radical neck dissection. After surgery, he complains of inability to abduct arm above shoulder level and shoulder drooping. The injured structure is:",o:["Phrenic nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Spinal accessory nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain"],a:3,e:"Spinal accessory nerve injury fits postoperative shoulder droop and impaired arm abduction after neck dissection. Trapezius wasting develops clinically progressively.<br><br>The accessory nerve traverses posterior triangle superficially and supplies trapezius muscle, making it highly vulnerable during cervical node clearance procedures.<br><br>Phrenic nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), vagus nerve (option C), and cervical sympathetic chain (option E) do not primarily control shoulder elevation. Therefore accessory nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with painless enlarging lateral neck mass anterior to sternocleidomastoid that transilluminates poorly. Fine needle aspiration reveals cholesterol crystals. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Dermoid cyst","Laryngocele"],a:0,e:"Branchial cyst fits a lateral cystic neck swelling containing cholesterol crystals on aspiration. Recurrent infections develop clinically after upper respiratory illnesses.<br><br>Second branchial cleft remnants commonly persist along upper anterior border of sternocleidomastoid, producing characteristic cystic lesions in young adults.<br><br>Cystic hygroma (option C), thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and laryngocele (option E) show different anatomical relationships. Therefore branchial cyst is likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The carotid body is located at the:",o:["Origin of vertebral artery","Bifurcation of common carotid artery","Root of subclavian artery","Jugular bulb","Thyrocervical trunk"],a:1,e:"Carotid body fits the chemoreceptor structure located near common carotid bifurcation. Reflex respiratory responses develop clinically during hypoxia.<br><br>Specialized glomus cells situated between internal and external carotid arteries monitor arterial oxygen and carbon dioxide concentrations continuously.<br><br>Origin of vertebral artery (option A), root of subclavian artery (option C), jugular bulb (option D), and thyrocervical trunk (option E) are incorrect sites. Therefore carotid bifurcation is correct.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina develops brawny swelling of submandibular region and tongue elevation. The primary involved fascial spaces are:",o:["Buccal and parotid spaces","Sublingual and submandibular spaces","Retropharyngeal and parapharyngeal spaces","Temporal and infratemporal spaces","Prevertebral and danger spaces"],a:1,e:"Sublingual and submandibular spaces fit the classic spread pattern of Ludwig angina. Airway compromise develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Odontogenic infections from mandibular molars penetrate fascial planes beneath tongue musculature and create diffuse cellulitis without localized abscess formation.<br><br>Buccal and parotid spaces (option A), retropharyngeal and parapharyngeal spaces (option C), temporal spaces (option D), and prevertebral spaces (option E) are less typical. Therefore sublingual and submandibular spaces are involved.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"During thyroid surgery, ligation of superior thyroid artery close to thyroid gland helps prevent injury to:",o:["External branch of superior laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:0,e:"External branch of superior laryngeal nerve preservation fits proper ligation technique during thyroidectomy. Voice fatigue develops clinically after injury.<br><br>This nerve accompanies superior thyroid vessels near upper thyroid pole and innervates cricothyroid muscle responsible for pitch modulation.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option C), lingual nerve (option D), and vagus nerve (option E) are less closely related to superior pole. Therefore superior laryngeal nerve is protected.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops unilateral ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis after cervical sympathectomy. This syndrome is called:",o:["Brown-Sequard syndrome","Horner syndrome","Frey syndrome","Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Eagle syndrome"],a:1,e:"Horner syndrome fits interruption of cervical sympathetic supply producing ptosis, miosis, and facial anhidrosis. Enophthalmos develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Sympathetic fibers ascending toward eye originate in thoracic spinal cord and travel through cervical sympathetic chain vulnerable during neck surgery.<br><br>Brown-Sequard syndrome (option A), Frey syndrome (option C), Ramsay Hunt syndrome (option D), and Eagle syndrome (option E) are unrelated conditions. Therefore Horner syndrome is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old woman presents with diffuse anterior neck swelling moving on swallowing. The swelling does not move on tongue protrusion. The structure of origin is most likely:",o:["Thyroglossal tract","Thyroid gland","Submental lymph nodes","Dermoid cyst","Branchial apparatus"],a:1,e:"Thyroid gland origin fits a swelling moving with deglutition but not with tongue protrusion. Pressure symptoms develop clinically in larger goiters.<br><br>The thyroid gland is attached to larynx and trachea through pretracheal fascia, causing upward movement during swallowing.<br><br>Thyroglossal tract (option A), submental nodes (option C), dermoid cyst (option D), and branchial remnants (option E) usually behave differently. Therefore thyroid origin is likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The floor of posterior triangle is formed mainly by all EXCEPT:",o:["Splenius capitis","Levator scapulae","Scalenus medius","Sternohyoid","Scalenus posterior"],a:3,e:"Sternohyoid does not contribute to posterior triangle floor. Infrahyoid muscles develop clinically in anterior neck compartment.<br><br>The posterior triangle floor is formed by prevertebral muscles covered with prevertebral fascia, including scalene and levator scapulae muscles.<br><br>Splenius capitis (option A), levator scapulae (option B), scalenus medius (option C), and scalenus posterior (option E) are true components. Therefore sternohyoid is excluded.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing central venous catheterization develops sudden dyspnea and elevated hemidiaphragm on chest X-ray. The injured nerve is:",o:["Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Accessory nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:2,e:"Phrenic nerve injury fits diaphragmatic paralysis after central venous access procedures. Breathlessness develops clinically particularly during exertion.<br><br>The phrenic nerve descends vertically over anterior scalene muscle close to subclavian vein and internal jugular venous access sites.<br><br>Vagus nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), accessory nerve (option D), and lingual nerve (option E) do not supply diaphragm. Therefore phrenic nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The deep cervical lymph nodes lie mainly along the:",o:["Internal jugular vein","External jugular vein","Facial artery","Thoracic duct","Anterior jugular vein"],a:0,e:"Internal jugular vein fits the anatomical relationship of deep cervical lymph nodes. Metastatic enlargement develops clinically in head and neck malignancies.<br><br>The jugular nodal chain drains extensive lymphatic territories from oral cavity, pharynx, larynx, thyroid, and scalp.<br><br>External jugular vein (option B), facial artery (option C), thoracic duct (option D), and anterior jugular vein (option E) are less relevant landmarks. Therefore internal jugular vein is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with stab wound in posterior triangle develops inability to turn head against resistance. The muscle affected is:",o:["Platysma","Sternocleidomastoid","Omohyoid","Digastric","Sternohyoid"],a:1,e:"Sternocleidomastoid weakness fits inability to rotate head against resistance after accessory nerve injury. Neck asymmetry develops clinically prominently.<br><br>The spinal accessory nerve supplies sternocleidomastoid before entering posterior triangle, making it vulnerable in penetrating trauma.<br><br>Platysma (option A), omohyoid (option C), digastric (option D), and sternohyoid (option E) perform different movements. Therefore sternocleidomastoid is affected.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn presents with soft fluctuant multiloculated swelling involving posterior triangle and axilla. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Lipoma","Lymphadenitis"],a:2,e:"Cystic hygroma fits a multiloculated congenital lymphatic swelling extending across fascial planes. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>These lesions represent congenital malformations of lymphatic sacs that fail to communicate normally with venous system.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), lipoma (option D), and lymphadenitis (option E) have different presentations. Therefore cystic hygroma is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic neck nodes develops hoarseness and aspiration after surgery. The injured nerve likely runs within:",o:["Carotid sheath","Prevertebral fascia","Investing fascia","Retropharyngeal space","Submandibular triangle only"],a:0,e:"Carotid sheath relation fits vagus nerve injury causing hoarseness and aspiration after neck surgery. Vocal cord weakness develops clinically significantly.<br><br>The vagus nerve descends within carotid sheath between carotid artery and internal jugular vein throughout the neck.<br><br>Prevertebral fascia (option B), investing fascia (option C), retropharyngeal space (option D), and submandibular triangle only (option E) do not enclose vagus nerve. Therefore carotid sheath is correct.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A neck swelling enlarging during coughing and Valsalva maneuver is most suggestive of:",o:["Laryngocele","Lipoma","Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst"],a:0,e:"Laryngocele fits a neck swelling enlarging with coughing or raised intralaryngeal pressure. Hoarseness develops clinically in internal lesions.<br><br>Air-filled dilation of laryngeal saccule communicates with laryngeal lumen and expands during activities increasing airway pressure.<br><br>Lipoma (option B), branchial cyst (option C), thyroglossal cyst (option D), and dermoid cyst (option E) usually do not vary with pressure. Therefore laryngocele is likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The pretracheal fascia encloses all EXCEPT:",o:["Thyroid gland","Trachea","Esophagus","Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Infrahyoid muscles"],a:3,e:"Sternocleidomastoid is not enclosed by pretracheal fascia. Neck muscle compartments develop clinically according to fascial organization.<br><br>Pretracheal fascia surrounds visceral cervical structures including thyroid gland, trachea, and infrahyoid muscles in anterior neck.<br><br>Thyroid gland (option A), trachea (option B), esophagus (option C), and infrahyoid muscles (option E) are enclosed within this fascial layer. Therefore sternocleidomastoid is excluded.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroid carcinoma develops enlarged left supraclavicular node. This node is called:",o:["Virchow node","Delphian node","Jugulodigastric node","Preauricular node","Submental node"],a:0,e:"Virchow node fits enlarged left supraclavicular metastatic node. Advanced malignancy develops clinically with distant lymphatic spread.<br><br>The thoracic duct drains into the left venous angle near this node, allowing abdominal and thoracic malignancies to metastasize there.<br><br>Delphian node (option B), jugulodigastric node (option C), preauricular node (option D), and submental node (option E) occupy different locations. Therefore Virchow node is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During tracheostomy, venous bleeding below thyroid isthmus most likely arises from:",o:["Facial vein","Inferior thyroid veins","External jugular vein","Lingual vein","Retromandibular vein"],a:1,e:"Inferior thyroid veins fit venous bleeding encountered below thyroid isthmus during tracheostomy. Airway obstruction develops clinically if hematoma enlarges.<br><br>These veins form a plexus anterior to trachea and drain lower thyroid poles into brachiocephalic venous system.<br><br>Facial vein (option A), external jugular vein (option C), lingual vein (option D), and retromandibular vein (option E) are less closely related. Therefore inferior thyroid veins are responsible.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with carotid body tumor presents with syncopal episodes due to hypersensitivity of:",o:["Carotid body","Carotid sinus","Jugular bulb","Vertebral artery","Cavernous sinus"],a:1,e:"Carotid sinus hypersensitivity fits recurrent syncopal attacks due to exaggerated baroreceptor reflexes. Bradycardia develops clinically during carotid stimulation.<br><br>Stretch receptors within carotid sinus wall regulate blood pressure through autonomic reflex pathways mediated mainly by glossopharyngeal nerve.<br><br>Carotid body (option A), jugular bulb (option C), vertebral artery (option D), and cavernous sinus (option E) are less related to syncope. Therefore carotid sinus is responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"The fascial layer forming the floor of posterior triangle and extending as axillary sheath is the:",o:["Prevertebral fascia","Investing fascia","Pretracheal fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia","Carotid sheath"],a:0,e:"Prevertebral fascia fits the layer extending into axilla around neurovascular bundle. Deep neck infections develop clinically along this plane.<br><br>This fascial layer covers vertebral muscles and contributes to axillary sheath surrounding brachial plexus and subclavian vessels.<br><br>Investing fascia (option B), pretracheal fascia (option C), buccopharyngeal fascia (option D), and carotid sheath (option E) serve different functions. Therefore prevertebral fascia is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with penetrating injury at root of neck develops milky drainage from wound after meals. The injured structure is most likely:",o:["Thoracic duct","Internal jugular vein","Vertebral artery","External jugular vein","Inferior thyroid artery"],a:0,e:"Thoracic duct injury fits postoperative milky drainage increasing after fatty meals. Nutritional depletion develops clinically if leak persists.<br><br>The thoracic duct arches in the left root of neck before emptying into venous angle between internal jugular and subclavian veins.<br><br>Internal jugular vein (option B), vertebral artery (option C), external jugular vein (option D), and inferior thyroid artery (option E) do not carry chyle. Therefore thoracic duct is injured.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 64-year-old man with carcinoma larynx undergoes radical neck dissection. Postoperatively, he develops winging of scapula and inability to elevate shoulder beyond horizontal. Which muscle has become functionally paralysed?",o:["Sternocleidomastoid","Levator scapulae","Trapezius","Rhomboid major","Serratus anterior"],a:2,e:"Trapezius paralysis fits postoperative shoulder dysfunction after accessory nerve injury during radical neck dissection. Shoulder drooping develops clinically prominently.<br><br>The spinal accessory nerve supplies trapezius after traversing posterior triangle superficially, making it highly vulnerable during clearance of cervical lymphatic tissue.<br><br>Sternocleidomastoid (option A), levator scapulae (option B), rhomboid major (option D), and serratus anterior (option E) are not primary muscles affected here. Therefore trapezius is paralysed.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A deep neck abscess located between buccopharyngeal fascia and alar fascia is situated in the:",o:["Pretracheal space","Retropharyngeal space","Danger space","Submandibular space","Carotid space"],a:1,e:"Retropharyngeal space fits the interval between buccopharyngeal and alar fascia. Dysphagia develops clinically due to posterior pharyngeal wall bulging.<br><br>This space contains retropharyngeal lymph nodes and extends from skull base to superior mediastinum where infection may spread downward.<br><br>Pretracheal space (option A), danger space (option C), submandibular space (option D), and carotid space (option E) occupy different fascial compartments. Therefore retropharyngeal space is correct.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"During thyroidectomy, the recurrent laryngeal nerve is most consistently related to:",o:["Inferior thyroid artery","Superior thyroid artery","Facial artery","Lingual artery","Common carotid artery"],a:0,e:"Inferior thyroid artery relation fits an important surgical landmark for recurrent laryngeal nerve identification. Hoarseness develops clinically after injury.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve usually ascends near branches of inferior thyroid artery within tracheoesophageal groove before entering larynx.<br><br>Superior thyroid artery (option B), facial artery (option C), lingual artery (option D), and common carotid artery (option E) are less constant relations. Therefore inferior thyroid artery is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with painful neck stiffness, dysphagia, muffled voice, and bulging posterior pharyngeal wall after fish bone injury. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Ludwig angina","Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Parotid abscess","Thyroglossal cyst infection"],a:2,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess fits dysphagia with posterior pharyngeal wall bulging after penetrating pharyngeal trauma. Airway obstruction develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Suppuration within retropharyngeal space pushes pharyngeal wall anteriorly and may descend into mediastinum if untreated.<br><br>Ludwig angina (option A), peritonsillar abscess (option B), parotid abscess (option D), and thyroglossal cyst infection (option E) present differently. Therefore retropharyngeal abscess is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The cervical sympathetic chain lies directly upon the:",o:["Investing fascia","Prevertebral fascia","Pretracheal fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia","Carotid sheath"],a:1,e:"Prevertebral fascia fits the anatomical plane supporting cervical sympathetic chain. Horner syndrome develops clinically after sympathetic interruption.<br><br>The sympathetic trunk descends vertically posterior to carotid sheath and anterior to longus muscles covered by prevertebral fascia.<br><br>Investing fascia (option A), pretracheal fascia (option C), buccopharyngeal fascia (option D), and carotid sheath (option E) do not directly support the chain. Therefore prevertebral fascia is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe bradycardia during carotid sinus massage. The afferent limb of this reflex is carried mainly by:",o:["Facial nerve","Vagus nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:2,e:"Glossopharyngeal nerve fits the afferent pathway of carotid sinus reflex. Syncope develops clinically in hypersensitive individuals.<br><br>Hering's nerve, a branch of glossopharyngeal nerve, transmits baroreceptor impulses from carotid sinus to medullary cardiovascular centers.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option E) are less important afferent pathways. Therefore glossopharyngeal nerve is correct.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A surgeon operating in posterior triangle accidentally damages a nerve running on anterior scalene muscle. The resulting complication will most likely be:",o:["Hemidiaphragm paralysis","Tongue deviation","Hoarseness","Facial asymmetry","Loss of taste sensation"],a:0,e:"Hemidiaphragm paralysis fits phrenic nerve injury on anterior scalene muscle. Dyspnea develops clinically especially during exertion.<br><br>The phrenic nerve descends vertically across anterior scalene before entering thorax to supply the diaphragm motor fibers.<br><br>Hoarseness (option C), tongue deviation (option B), facial asymmetry (option D), and taste loss (option E) result from injuries to other nerves. Therefore diaphragmatic paralysis occurs.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old man presents with cystic neck swelling that becomes prominent while straining and decreases at rest. CT scan demonstrates air-filled sac communicating with laryngeal ventricle. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Laryngocele","Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst"],a:2,e:"Laryngocele fits an air-filled swelling enlarging during raised intralaryngeal pressure. Hoarseness develops clinically in internal lesions.<br><br>Dilatation of laryngeal saccule maintains communication with laryngeal lumen, causing expansion during coughing and straining maneuvers.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), cystic hygroma (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option D), and dermoid cyst (option E) are not air-filled. Therefore laryngocele is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common congenital midline neck swelling is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Hemangioma","Sebaceous cyst"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cyst fits the commonest congenital midline neck swelling. Infection develops clinically during childhood or early adulthood.<br><br>Persistence of thyroglossal duct remnants between foramen cecum and thyroid gland produces cystic midline masses.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option B), cystic hygroma (option C), hemangioma (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) are less common midline lesions. Therefore thyroglossal cyst predominates.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During neck dissection, the structure most vulnerable at Erb's point is:",o:["Cervical plexus branches","Hypoglossal nerve","Facial artery","Thoracic duct","Lingual nerve"],a:0,e:"Cervical plexus branches fit structures emerging at Erb's point along posterior border of sternocleidomastoid. Sensory deficits develop clinically after injury.<br><br>Cutaneous nerves supplying neck, ear, and shoulder emerge superficially at this nerve point in the posterior triangle.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option B), facial artery (option C), thoracic duct (option D), and lingual nerve (option E) do not emerge here. Therefore cervical plexus branches are vulnerable.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced thyroid carcinoma develops fixation of vocal cord. The most likely mechanism is involvement of:",o:["Superior laryngeal nerve","External carotid artery","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Internal jugular vein"],a:2,e:"Recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement fits vocal cord fixation in advanced thyroid malignancy. Hoarseness develops clinically early.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve courses closely behind thyroid gland within tracheoesophageal groove before entering larynx.<br><br>Superior laryngeal nerve (option A), external carotid artery (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and internal jugular vein (option E) do not commonly fix vocal cords. Therefore recurrent laryngeal nerve is implicated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops collection deep to investing fascia but superficial to pretracheal fascia. The abscess lies within the:",o:["Visceral compartment","Superficial cervical space","Retropharyngeal space","Danger space","Carotid space"],a:1,e:"Superficial cervical space fits infection located beneath investing fascia but outside deeper visceral compartments. Neck swelling develops clinically prominently.<br><br>The investing layer encloses superficial muscular and glandular structures while separating them from deeper fascial planes.<br><br>Visceral compartment (option A), retropharyngeal space (option C), danger space (option D), and carotid space (option E) occupy deeper locations. Therefore superficial cervical space is correct.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with carcinoma tongue presents with metastatic node at junction of posterior belly of digastric and internal jugular vein. This node is:",o:["Jugulodigastric node","Virchow node","Delphian node","Jugulo-omohyoid node","Prelaryngeal node"],a:0,e:"Jugulodigastric node fits upper deep cervical nodal enlargement in oral malignancies. Neck metastasis develops clinically early.<br><br>This node lies beneath sternocleidomastoid near posterior belly of digastric and drains tonsillar and oral cavity regions.<br><br>Delphian node (option C), Virchow node (option B), jugulo-omohyoid node (option D), and prelaryngeal node (option E) occupy different locations. Therefore jugulodigastric node is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe odontogenic infection develops bilateral woody swelling of submandibular region without fluctuation. The condition is:",o:["Retropharyngeal abscess","Ludwig angina","Peritonsillar abscess","Branchial cyst infection","Suppurative thyroiditis"],a:1,e:"Ludwig angina fits bilateral brawny cellulitis of submandibular spaces arising from dental infection. Airway obstruction develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Unlike localized abscesses, this cellulitis spreads diffusely through fascial planes producing hard indurated swelling and tongue elevation.<br><br>Retropharyngeal abscess (option A), peritonsillar abscess (option C), branchial cyst infection (option D), and suppurative thyroiditis (option E) differ clinically. Therefore Ludwig angina is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The carotid sheath is formed by contributions from all deep cervical fascia layers EXCEPT:",o:["Investing fascia","Pretracheal fascia","Prevertebral fascia","Superficial fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia"],a:3,e:"Superficial fascia does not contribute to carotid sheath formation. Deep neurovascular structures develop clinically within specialized fascial condensations.<br><br>The carotid sheath receives fascial contributions from investing, pretracheal, and prevertebral layers surrounding vascular structures.<br><br>Investing fascia (option A), pretracheal fascia (option B), prevertebral fascia (option C), and buccopharyngeal fascia (option E) are related deep fascial layers. Therefore superficial fascia is excluded.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with posterior triangle stab wound develops loss of sensation over angle of mandible and lower auricle. The injured nerve is:",o:["Lesser occipital nerve","Supraclavicular nerve","Transverse cervical nerve","Great auricular nerve","Auriculotemporal nerve"],a:3,e:"Great auricular nerve injury fits sensory loss over lower auricle and mandibular angle. Numbness develops clinically after superficial cervical trauma.<br><br>This cervical plexus branch ascends over sternocleidomastoid toward parotid and auricular regions carrying cutaneous sensory fibers.<br><br>Lesser occipital nerve (option A), transverse cervical nerve (option C), supraclavicular nerve (option B), and auriculotemporal nerve (option E) supply different areas. Therefore great auricular nerve is affected.<br><br><em>(Gray's Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroid swelling presents with inspiratory stridor worsened in supine position. The most likely explanation is:",o:["Recurrent laryngeal nerve irritation only","Pharyngeal edema","Esophageal obstruction","Tracheal compression","Cervical sympathectomy"],a:3,e:"Tracheal compression fits positional stridor caused by large thyroid masses. Respiratory distress develops clinically especially during recumbency.<br><br>The thyroid gland lies directly anterior and lateral to trachea, allowing enlarging goiters to narrow airway lumen mechanically.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal irritation only (option A), esophageal obstruction (option C), pharyngeal edema (option B), and sympathectomy (option E) do not fully explain stridor. Therefore tracheal compression is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During emergency tracheostomy in a child, the structure most at risk because of high position is:",o:["Thyroid isthmus","Inferior thyroid veins","Thymus","Internal jugular vein","Vertebral artery"],a:2,e:"Thymus vulnerability fits pediatric tracheostomy because cervical extension of thymic tissue lies relatively higher in children. Hemorrhage develops clinically if injured.<br><br>The infant neck is shorter and deeper structures are crowded, making lower cervical structures anatomically closer to tracheostomy field.<br><br>Thyroid isthmus (option A), inferior thyroid veins (option B), internal jugular vein (option D), and vertebral artery (option E) are important but less distinctive pediatric risks. Therefore thymus is at risk.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The jugulo-omohyoid node is particularly important in metastasis from:",o:["Nasopharynx","Tongue","Thyroid gland","Larynx","External ear"],a:1,e:"Jugulo-omohyoid node fits an important nodal station in tongue carcinoma metastasis. Cervical spread develops clinically relatively early.<br><br>This lower deep cervical node lies near intermediate tendon of omohyoid and receives lymphatic drainage from tongue.<br><br>Nasopharynx (option A), thyroid gland (option C), larynx (option D), and external ear (option E) drain predominantly to different nodal groups. Therefore tongue is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with descending necrotizing mediastinitis secondary to neck infection most likely had initial spread through the:",o:["Submandibular space","Retropharyngeal and danger spaces","Carotid bifurcation","Thyroid capsule","Parotid fascia"],a:1,e:"Retropharyngeal and danger spaces fit pathways for rapid descent of cervical infection into mediastinum. Septic shock develops clinically with delayed treatment.<br><br>These fascial planes extend directly from skull base into thoracic cavity without anatomical barriers limiting infection spread.<br><br>Submandibular space (option A), carotid bifurcation (option C), thyroid capsule (option D), and parotid fascia (option E) are less direct routes. Therefore retropharyngeal and danger spaces are responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 56-year-old man undergoes radical neck dissection for metastatic cervical nodes. After surgery, he cannot shrug his shoulder and has difficulty abducting arm above 90°. Which nerve was most likely sacrificed?",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Spinal accessory nerve","Lingual nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:2,e:"Spinal accessory nerve injury fits postoperative shoulder dysfunction after radical neck dissection. Trapezius wasting develops clinically within weeks.<br><br>The accessory nerve traverses the posterior triangle superficially after supplying sternocleidomastoid, making it highly vulnerable during lymph node clearance procedures.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) do not primarily supply trapezius. Therefore spinal accessory nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The carotid sheath contains all of the following EXCEPT:",o:["Internal jugular vein","Vagus nerve","Common carotid artery","Cervical sympathetic chain","Internal carotid artery"],a:3,e:"Cervical sympathetic chain does not lie within carotid sheath. Horner syndrome develops clinically when these fibers are damaged.<br><br>The sympathetic trunk runs posterior to carotid sheath over prevertebral fascia, whereas carotid sheath encloses major vascular and neural structures.<br><br>Internal jugular vein (option A), vagus nerve (option B), common carotid artery (option C), and internal carotid artery (option E) are true contents. Therefore sympathetic chain is excluded.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with thyroid swelling develops hoarseness. The most likely involved nerve is:",o:["External branch of superior laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Greater auricular nerve"],a:3,e:"Recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement fits hoarseness associated with thyroid enlargement. Vocal cord paralysis develops clinically after compression or infiltration.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within tracheoesophageal groove and maintains close anatomical relation to thyroid gland.<br><br>External branch of superior laryngeal nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option C), glossopharyngeal nerve (option B), and greater auricular nerve (option E) are less likely causes. Therefore recurrent laryngeal nerve is affected.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with midline neck swelling that moves upward on tongue protrusion. The diagnosis is most likely:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Sebaceous cyst","Dermoid cyst"],a:1,e:"Thyroglossal cyst fits a midline neck swelling moving during tongue protrusion. Recurrent infection develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Persistence of thyroglossal duct attachment to foramen cecum explains movement during swallowing and tongue movement.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), cystic hygroma (option C), sebaceous cyst (option D), and dermoid cyst (option E) usually lack this characteristic mobility. Therefore thyroglossal cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina is at greatest immediate risk of:",o:["Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Meningitis","Facial nerve paralysis","Airway obstruction","Hearing loss"],a:3,e:"Airway obstruction fits the most dangerous complication of Ludwig angina. Tongue elevation develops clinically due to submandibular cellulitis.<br><br>Diffuse infection of sublingual and submandibular spaces rapidly narrows upper airway by posterior displacement of oral floor structures.<br><br>Cavernous sinus thrombosis (option A), facial paralysis (option C), meningitis (option B), and hearing loss (option E) are less immediate threats. Therefore airway compromise is most feared.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The phrenic nerve descends on the surface of:",o:["Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Longus colli muscle","Levator scapulae muscle","Scalenus anterior muscle","Trapezius muscle"],a:3,e:"Scalenus anterior muscle fits the anatomical course of phrenic nerve in neck. Diaphragmatic paralysis develops clinically after injury.<br><br>The phrenic nerve descends vertically across anterior scalene beneath prevertebral fascia before entering thorax between major vessels.<br><br>Sternocleidomastoid (option A), levator scapulae (option C), longus colli (option B), and trapezius (option E) are unrelated surfaces. Therefore scalenus anterior is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis following cervical node metastasis. The involved structure is:",o:["Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain","Accessory nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:2,e:"Cervical sympathetic chain involvement fits Horner syndrome with ptosis, miosis, and facial anhidrosis. Ipsilateral facial flushing develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Sympathetic fibers supplying ocular muscles and sweat glands ascend through cervical sympathetic ganglia located behind carotid sheath.<br><br>Vagus nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), accessory nerve (option D), and lingual nerve (option E) do not produce Horner syndrome. Therefore sympathetic chain is involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common congenital lateral neck cyst is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Ranula","Sebaceous cyst"],a:1,e:"Branchial cyst fits the commonest congenital lateral neck cystic swelling. Secondary infection develops clinically in young adults.<br><br>Most branchial cysts arise from remnants of second branchial cleft along anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option C), ranula (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) are less typical lateral lesions. Therefore branchial cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During tracheostomy, excessive inferior dissection may injure the:",o:["Facial artery","Superficial temporal artery","Lingual artery","Inferior thyroid veins","External carotid artery"],a:3,e:"Inferior thyroid veins fit important vascular structures at risk during low tracheostomy. Significant hemorrhage develops clinically after injury.<br><br>These veins form a plexus anterior to trachea before draining into brachiocephalic venous system near thoracic inlet.<br><br>Facial artery (option A), lingual artery (option C), superficial temporal artery (option B), and external carotid artery (option E) are less closely related. Therefore inferior thyroid veins are vulnerable.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A pulsatile neck swelling movable horizontally but fixed vertically is characteristic of:",o:["Branchial cyst","Lipoma","Thyroglossal cyst","Carotid body tumor","Lymphangioma"],a:3,e:"Carotid body tumor fits a pulsatile swelling with side-to-side mobility but restricted vertical movement. Bruit develops clinically over larger lesions.<br><br>The tumor arises at carotid bifurcation where attachment to carotid vessels limits superior-inferior displacement.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option C), lipoma (option B), and lymphangioma (option E) are usually nonpulsatile. Therefore carotid body tumor is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops unilateral diaphragmatic paralysis after neck surgery. The injured nerve arises mainly from:",o:["C1,C2","C3-C5","C5,C7","C2,C4","T1,T3"],a:1,e:"C3-C5 roots fit the origin of phrenic nerve supplying diaphragm. Respiratory compromise develops clinically after injury.<br><br>The classical anatomical mnemonic \"C3, 4, 5 keep the diaphragm alive\" reflects major cervical spinal contributions to phrenic nerve fibers.<br><br>C1,C2 (option A), C5,C7 (option C), C2,C4 (option D), and T1,T3 (option E) are inaccurate combinations. Therefore C3-C5 is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The deep cervical fascia enclosing sternocleidomastoid and trapezius is the:",o:["Pretracheal fascia","Investing fascia","Prevertebral fascia","Buccopharyngeal fascia","Alar fascia"],a:1,e:"Investing fascia fits the fascial layer surrounding sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles. Surgical neck planes develop clinically relative to this layer.<br><br>This superficial layer of deep cervical fascia forms a collar around neck and contributes to parotid and submandibular capsules.<br><br>Pretracheal fascia (option A), prevertebral fascia (option C), buccopharyngeal fascia (option D), and alar fascia (option E) cover deeper compartments. Therefore investing fascia is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retropharyngeal abscess is most likely to present with:",o:["Torticollis and dysphagia","Conductive hearing loss only","Facial asymmetry","Epistaxis","Trismus without dysphagia"],a:0,e:"Torticollis and dysphagia fit retropharyngeal abscess causing painful neck stiffness. Airway compromise develops clinically in severe infections.<br><br>Inflammation within retropharyngeal space causes posterior pharyngeal wall bulging and reflex neck extension to reduce discomfort.<br><br>Conductive hearing loss only (option B), facial asymmetry (option C), epistaxis (option D), and isolated trismus (option E) are less typical. Therefore torticollis with dysphagia is characteristic.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The ansa cervicalis supplies all EXCEPT:",o:["Sternohyoid","Sternothyroid","Omohyoid","Thyrohyoid","Trapezius"],a:4,e:"Trapezius is not supplied by ansa cervicalis. Shoulder weakness develops clinically after accessory nerve injury instead.<br><br>Ansa cervicalis innervates most infrahyoid muscles, while thyrohyoid receives fibers traveling with hypoglossal nerve.<br><br>Sternohyoid (option A), sternothyroid (option B), omohyoid (option C), and thyrohyoid (option D) are related infrahyoid muscles. Therefore trapezius is excluded.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A surgeon palpates a node at the junction of posterior belly of digastric and internal jugular vein. This node is the:",o:["Jugulodigastric node","Jugulo-omohyoid node","Delphian node","Virchow node","Pretracheal node"],a:0,e:"Jugulodigastric node fits the important upper deep cervical node near posterior belly of digastric. Tonsillar infections develop clinically with enlargement here.<br><br>This node drains pharyngeal and oral cavity regions and frequently enlarges in head and neck malignancies.<br><br>Delphian node (option C), jugulo-omohyoid node (option B), Virchow node (option D), and pretracheal node (option E) occupy different locations. Therefore jugulodigastric node is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops loss of sensation over angle of mandible after superficial neck surgery. Which nerve was most likely injured?",o:["Lesser occipital nerve","Auriculotemporal nerve","Lingual nerve","Great auricular nerve","Supraclavicular nerve"],a:3,e:"Great auricular nerve injury fits numbness over angle of mandible and lower auricle. Sensory deficits develop clinically after parotid or neck surgery.<br><br>This cervical plexus branch crosses sternocleidomastoid superficially toward parotid gland and ear region.<br><br>Lesser occipital nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option C), auriculotemporal nerve (option B), and supraclavicular nerve (option E) supply different territories. Therefore great auricular nerve is affected.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with large goiter develops dysphagia. The symptom is due to compression of:",o:["Carotid artery","Esophagus","Internal jugular vein","Cervical sympathetic chain","Thoracic duct"],a:1,e:"Esophageal compression fits dysphagia caused by large thyroid enlargement. Progressive swallowing difficulty develops clinically in retrosternal goiters.<br><br>The cervical esophagus lies posterior to trachea and thyroid gland, making it susceptible to pressure from enlarging thyroid masses.<br><br>Carotid artery (option A), internal jugular vein (option C), cervical sympathetic chain (option D), and thoracic duct (option E) are less likely causes. Therefore esophagus is compressed.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with congenital muscular torticollis. The affected muscle is:",o:["Trapezius","Digastric","Omohyoid","Sternocleidomastoid","Platysma"],a:3,e:"Sternocleidomastoid fibrosis fits congenital muscular torticollis. Chin deviation develops clinically away from affected side.<br><br>Birth trauma or intrauterine malposition may produce fibrosis and shortening of sternocleidomastoid muscle in infancy.<br><br>Trapezius (option A), omohyoid (option C), digastric (option B), and platysma (option E) are not usual causes. Therefore sternocleidomastoid is affected.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neck trauma develops chylous fistula. The injured structure most likely enters venous system at junction of:",o:["External jugular and subclavian veins","Internal jugular and subclavian veins","Facial and lingual veins","Common carotid and internal jugular veins","Vertebral and brachiocephalic veins"],a:1,e:"Internal jugular and subclavian venous junction fits thoracic duct termination. Milky drainage develops clinically after injury.<br><br>The thoracic duct arches in left root of neck before emptying into left venous angle near brachiocephalic formation.<br><br>External jugular and subclavian veins (option A), facial and lingual veins (option C), carotid and jugular structures (option D), and vertebral junctions (option E) are inaccurate. Therefore internal jugular-subclavian junction is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neck abscess develops descending necrotizing mediastinitis. The infection most likely spread through the:",o:["Submandibular space only","Parotid fascia","Carotid sheath only","Danger space","Thyroid capsule"],a:3,e:"Danger space spread fits rapid extension of cervical infection into mediastinum. Septic shock develops clinically with delayed treatment.<br><br>The danger space extends uninterrupted from skull base to diaphragm between alar and prevertebral fascial layers.<br><br>Submandibular space only (option A), carotid sheath only (option C), parotid fascia (option B), and thyroid capsule (option E) are less direct pathways. Therefore danger space is responsible.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 24-year-old woman presents with a soft multiloculated swelling in the posterior triangle of neck since infancy. The swelling brilliantly transilluminates and enlarges during upper respiratory infections. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Cystic hygroma","Branchial cyst","Carotid body tumor","Lipoma","Dermoid cyst"],a:0,e:"Cystic hygroma fits a congenital multiloculated lymphatic lesion occurring in posterior triangle. Airway compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>Embryological failure of lymphatic sacs to communicate properly with venous channels leads to diffuse cystic spaces crossing fascial planes.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option B), carotid body tumor (option C), lipoma (option D), and dermoid cyst (option E) are less transilluminant and usually more localized. Therefore cystic hygroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless fluctuant swelling located along the anterior border of sternocleidomastoid in a young adult is most likely:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Sebaceous cyst","Ranula","Dermoid cyst"],a:1,e:"Branchial cyst fits a lateral neck swelling situated near the anterior border of sternocleidomastoid. Secondary infection develops clinically after upper respiratory illnesses.<br><br>Most lesions originate from remnants of the second branchial cleft and present during adolescence or early adulthood.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), sebaceous cyst (option C), ranula (option D), and dermoid cyst (option E) usually occur in different anatomical locations. Therefore branchial cyst is likely.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 62-year-old smoker presents with hard fixed cervical lymph nodes associated with weight loss and dysphagia. The most likely pathology is:",o:["Reactive lymphadenopathy","Tuberculous lymphadenitis","Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma","Lipoma","Lymphangioma"],a:2,e:"Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma fits hard fixed cervical nodes in elderly smokers. Progressive constitutional symptoms develop clinically with advanced disease.<br><br>Upper aerodigestive tract cancers commonly metastasize through rich cervical lymphatic channels producing firm infiltrative nodal masses.<br><br>Reactive lymphadenopathy (option A), tuberculous lymphadenitis (option B), lipoma (option D), and lymphangioma (option E) are usually softer or mobile. Therefore metastatic carcinoma is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A pulsatile neck swelling that moves horizontally but not vertically is characteristic of:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Lipoma","Carotid body tumor","Hemangioma"],a:3,e:"Carotid body tumor fits a pulsatile swelling with side-to-side mobility but restricted vertical movement. Bruit develops clinically in vascular lesions.<br><br>The tumor arises from paraganglionic tissue at carotid bifurcation where fixation to arterial walls limits superior-inferior displacement.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), lipoma (option C), and hemangioma (option E) lack this classic mobility pattern. Therefore carotid body tumor is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Milky drainage from neck wound after left-sided radical neck dissection most likely indicates injury to:",o:["Thoracic duct","Inferior thyroid vein","Internal jugular vein","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","External carotid artery"],a:0,e:"Thoracic duct injury fits postoperative chylous fistula following neck surgery. Nutritional depletion develops clinically if leakage persists.<br><br>The thoracic duct arches in the left root of neck before draining into junction of subclavian and internal jugular veins.<br><br>Inferior thyroid vein (option B), internal jugular vein (option C), recurrent laryngeal nerve (option D), and external carotid artery (option E) do not carry chyle. Therefore thoracic duct is injured.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A midline neck swelling moving upward during swallowing and tongue protrusion is most suggestive of:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Sebaceous cyst","Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Lipoma"],a:3,e:"Thyroglossal cyst fits a midline swelling moving with tongue protrusion. Infection develops clinically frequently during childhood.<br><br>Persistence of embryological thyroglossal tract attached to foramen cecum explains characteristic movement during tongue motion.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option A), sebaceous cyst (option B), branchial cyst (option C), and lipoma (option E) lack this distinctive mobility. Therefore thyroglossal cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A chronic smoker presents with hoarseness and enlarged supraclavicular cervical node. The most likely primary lesion is:",o:["Laryngeal carcinoma","Pituitary adenoma","Osteosarcoma","Meningioma","Acoustic neuroma"],a:0,e:"Laryngeal carcinoma fits cervical nodal metastasis associated with persistent hoarseness in smokers. Airway symptoms develop clinically later.<br><br>Supraglottic laryngeal tumors possess abundant lymphatic drainage leading to early cervical nodal spread.<br><br>Pituitary adenoma (option B), osteosarcoma (option C), meningioma (option D), and acoustic neuroma (option E) rarely present with cervical metastasis. Therefore laryngeal carcinoma is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant neck mass in adults is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Lymphangioma","Metastatic lymph node","Thyroglossal cyst","Lipoma"],a:2,e:"Metastatic lymph node fits the commonest malignant neck swelling in adults. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced malignancies.<br><br>Cervical lymph nodes drain mucosal surfaces of upper aerodigestive tract where squamous carcinomas commonly originate.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), lymphangioma (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option D), and lipoma (option E) are benign lesions. Therefore metastatic node predominates.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with fever, drooling, bilateral submandibular swelling, and elevation of tongue. The diagnosis is most likely:",o:["Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Ludwig angina","Acute parotitis","Suppurative thyroiditis"],a:2,e:"Ludwig angina fits diffuse cellulitis involving submandibular and sublingual spaces. Airway obstruction develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Odontogenic infections from lower molars commonly spread through fascial planes producing tense brawny swelling of floor of mouth.<br><br>Peritonsillar abscess (option A), retropharyngeal abscess (option B), acute parotitis (option D), and suppurative thyroiditis (option E) present differently. Therefore Ludwig angina is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A soft mobile neck swelling showing \"slip sign\" during palpation is most characteristic of:",o:["Metastatic lymph node","Branchial cyst","Lipoma","Carotid body tumor","Dermoid cyst"],a:2,e:"Lipoma fits a soft mobile swelling with slipping sensation during palpation. Cosmetic deformity develops clinically gradually over years.<br><br>Benign proliferation of mature adipose tissue enclosed within a delicate capsule creates characteristic doughy consistency.<br><br>Metastatic lymph node (option A), branchial cyst (option B), carotid body tumor (option D), and dermoid cyst (option E) feel less freely mobile. Therefore lipoma is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cervical metastatic disease develops ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis. Which structure is most likely involved?",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Facial nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain","Lingual nerve"],a:3,e:"Cervical sympathetic chain involvement fits Horner syndrome in advanced neck malignancy. Ipsilateral facial flushing develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>The sympathetic trunk lies posterior to carotid sheath and may be infiltrated by deep cervical metastatic nodes.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), facial nerve (option C), and lingual nerve (option E) do not produce Horner syndrome. Therefore sympathetic chain is involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A neck swelling enlarging during coughing and containing air on imaging is most likely:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Hemangioma","Dermoid cyst","Laryngocele"],a:4,e:"Laryngocele fits an air-filled swelling increasing during coughing or Valsalva maneuver. Hoarseness develops clinically in internal lesions.<br><br>Dilatation of laryngeal saccule communicating with laryngeal lumen allows expansion during raised intralaryngeal pressure.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), hemangioma (option C), and dermoid cyst (option D) are not air-containing lesions. Therefore laryngocele is correct.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A hard enlarged left supraclavicular node associated with abdominal malignancy is called:",o:["Virchow node","Delphian node","Jugulo-omohyoid node","Prelaryngeal node","Jugulodigastric node"],a:0,e:"Virchow node fits metastatic enlargement of left supraclavicular lymph node. Advanced abdominal malignancy develops clinically with distant lymphatic spread.<br><br>The thoracic duct drains abdominal lymphatic flow into left venous angle near this nodal region.<br><br>Delphian node (option B), jugulo-omohyoid node (option C), prelaryngeal node (option D), and jugulodigastric node (option E) occupy different sites. Therefore Virchow node is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A brilliantly transilluminant neck swelling crossing tissue planes is most likely:",o:["Metastatic lymph node","Carotid aneurysm","Branchial cyst","Lipoma","Cystic hygroma"],a:4,e:"Cystic hygroma fits a brilliantly transilluminant lesion extending across fascial planes. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in large lesions.<br><br>Congenital lymphatic malformations contain interconnected endothelial-lined spaces filled with lymphatic fluid.<br><br>Metastatic lymph node (option A), carotid aneurysm (option B), branchial cyst (option C), and lipoma (option D) usually do not transilluminate brilliantly. Therefore cystic hygroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ulcerative lesion in pyriform fossa develops enlargement of upper deep cervical node. The involved node is most likely:",o:["Delphian node","Submental node","Occipital node","Jugulodigastric node","Preauricular node"],a:3,e:"Jugulodigastric node fits upper deep cervical metastasis from hypopharyngeal malignancies. Dysphagia develops clinically commonly.<br><br>The pyriform fossa possesses extensive lymphatic drainage into upper deep cervical nodal chains.<br><br>Delphian node (option A), occipital node (option C), submental node (option B), and preauricular node (option E) drain different regions. Therefore jugulodigastric node is involved.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common benign soft tissue tumor of neck in adults is:",o:["Lipoma","Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Laryngocele"],a:0,e:"Lipoma fits the commonest benign soft tissue tumor occurring in adult neck. Slow painless enlargement develops clinically over years.<br><br>Benign proliferation of mature adipocytes within a thin fibrous capsule produces characteristic soft consistency and mobility.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option C), cystic hygroma (option D), and laryngocele (option E) are congenital or developmental lesions. Therefore lipoma is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Recurrence after surgery for thyroglossal cyst usually results from failure to remove:",o:["Omohyoid tendon","Superior thyroid artery","Sternocleidomastoid fascia","Central hyoid bone segment","Submandibular gland"],a:3,e:"Central hyoid bone removal fits the essential principle of Sistrunk operation. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>The thyroglossal tract passes through or behind the body of hyoid bone during embryological thyroid descent.<br><br>Omohyoid tendon (option A), sternocleidomastoid fascia (option C), superior thyroid artery (option B), and submandibular gland (option E) are unrelated structures. Therefore central hyoid removal is necessary.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A metastatic cervical node from an unknown primary in an elderly smoker is most commonly due to:",o:["Osteogenic sarcoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Thyroglossal duct carcinoma","Hemangioma","Fibrosarcoma"],a:1,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits the commonest source of metastatic cervical nodes in elderly smokers. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>The upper aerodigestive tract is lined predominantly by squamous epithelium highly susceptible to tobacco-related malignant transformation.<br><br>Osteogenic sarcoma (option A), thyroglossal duct carcinoma (option C), hemangioma (option D), and fibrosarcoma (option E) are far less common causes. Therefore squamous carcinoma predominates.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Matted cervical lymph nodes with evening fever and cold abscess formation are most suggestive of:",o:["Lipoma","Metastatic carcinoma","Branchial cyst","Tuberculous lymphadenitis","Carotid body tumor"],a:3,e:"Tuberculous lymphadenitis fits matted cervical nodes associated with constitutional symptoms. Sinus formation develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Granulomatous inflammation with caseation causes periadenitis leading to adherence between lymph nodes.<br><br>Lipoma (option A), metastatic carcinoma (option B), branchial cyst (option C), and carotid body tumor (option E) do not typically produce matted nodes with fever. Therefore tuberculosis is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Syncope precipitated by palpation of carotid body tumor is due to hypersensitivity of the:",o:["Jugular bulb","Carotid body","Cavernous sinus","Vertebral artery","Carotid sinus"],a:4,e:"Carotid sinus hypersensitivity fits syncope triggered by manipulation of carotid body tumors. Reflex bradycardia develops clinically during neck pressure.<br><br>Stretch receptors within carotid sinus wall mediate exaggerated vagal cardiovascular reflexes when stimulated externally.<br><br>Jugular bulb (option A), carotid body (option B), cavernous sinus (option C), and vertebral artery (option D) are less directly related to syncope. Therefore carotid sinus is responsible.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 48-year-old man presents with a slowly enlarging painless neck mass deep to sternocleidomastoid. FNAC reveals metastatic squamous cells, but no obvious primary lesion is identified. The most appropriate next step is:",o:["Immediate radical neck dissection","Observation for 6 months","Search for occult primary in upper aerodigestive tract","Start antituberculous therapy","Excision biopsy under local anesthesia"],a:2,e:"Search for occult primary fits management of metastatic cervical nodes with unknown primary. Dysphagia or hoarseness develops clinically in hidden mucosal tumors.<br><br>Most metastatic squamous cervical nodes originate from upper aerodigestive tract sites such as nasopharynx, oropharynx, hypopharynx, or larynx.<br><br>Immediate radical neck dissection (option A), observation (option B), empirical antituberculous therapy (option D), and excision biopsy (option E) are less appropriate initially. Therefore occult primary evaluation is essential.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A congenital neck swelling situated in the midline and attached to the hyoid bone is most likely derived from:",o:["Second branchial cleft","Thymopharyngeal tract","First pharyngeal pouch","Cervical sinus","Thyroglossal duct"],a:4,e:"Thyroglossal duct remnants fit congenital midline cystic neck swellings attached to hyoid region. Infection develops clinically during childhood.<br><br>Embryological descent of thyroid gland from foramen cecum leaves epithelial remnants capable of cyst formation.<br><br>Second branchial cleft (option A), first pharyngeal pouch (option C), cervical sinus (option D), and thymopharyngeal tract (option B) produce different anomalies. Therefore thyroglossal duct is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with malignant cervical lymphadenopathy develops severe shoulder droop after surgery. Paralysis of which muscle best explains this deformity?",o:["Trapezius","Platysma","Sternohyoid","Levator scapulae","Digastric"],a:0,e:"Trapezius paralysis fits shoulder droop following accessory nerve injury during neck dissection. Difficulty abducting arm develops clinically prominently.<br><br>The spinal accessory nerve supplies trapezius after crossing posterior triangle superficially where it becomes vulnerable surgically.<br><br>Sternohyoid (option C), platysma (option B), levator scapulae (option D), and digastric (option E) do not produce marked shoulder drooping. Therefore trapezius paralysis explains findings.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with a soft compressible neck swelling that increases in size during crying and Valsalva maneuver. Imaging reveals a venous malformation. The swelling most likely enlarges because of:",o:["Increased arterial flow","Lymphatic obstruction","Raised intracranial pressure","Increased venous pressure","Salivary hypersecretion"],a:3,e:"Increased venous pressure fits enlargement of venous malformations during straining or crying. Distension develops clinically intermittently.<br><br>Raised intrathoracic pressure impedes venous return temporarily causing dilation of compliant venous channels within lesion.<br><br>Increased arterial flow (option A), lymphatic obstruction (option B), raised intracranial pressure (option C), and salivary hypersecretion (option E) are less relevant mechanisms. Therefore venous pressure is responsible.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neck malignancy develops hoarseness due to unilateral vocal cord paralysis. Which nerve is most likely involved?",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","External branch of superior laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Great auricular nerve"],a:2,e:"Recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement fits unilateral vocal cord paralysis associated with neck malignancy. Aspiration develops clinically in severe cases.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends within tracheoesophageal groove and supplies nearly all intrinsic laryngeal muscles.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), superior laryngeal nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and great auricular nerve (option E) do not directly abduct vocal cords. Therefore recurrent laryngeal nerve is involved.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site for branchial cyst is along the:",o:["Posterior border of trapezius","Midline over thyroid cartilage","Anterior border of sternocleidomastoid","Floor of mouth","Submental triangle"],a:2,e:"Anterior border of sternocleidomastoid fits the typical location of branchial cysts. Infection develops clinically after respiratory illnesses.<br><br>Most branchial cysts arise from second branchial cleft remnants located in upper lateral neck.<br><br>Posterior border of trapezius (option A), midline thyroid region (option B), floor of mouth (option D), and submental triangle (option E) are atypical sites. Therefore anterior sternocleidomastoid border is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with rapidly enlarging painful neck mass associated with fever and overlying skin erythema. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Metastatic lymph node","Acute suppurative lymphadenitis","Carotid body tumor","Lipoma","Laryngocele"],a:1,e:"Acute suppurative lymphadenitis fits painful inflamed cervical swelling associated with systemic infection. Fluctuation develops clinically after abscess formation.<br><br>Bacterial infection of draining lymph nodes produces edema, neutrophilic infiltration, and tenderness.<br><br>Metastatic lymph node (option A), carotid body tumor (option C), lipoma (option D), and laryngocele (option E) are generally painless initially. Therefore suppurative lymphadenitis is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A cystic lesion arising from remnants of cervical sinus is most likely:",o:["Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Ranula","Sebaceous cyst"],a:0,e:"Branchial cyst fits persistence of embryological cervical sinus remnants. Painless lateral neck swelling develops clinically in young adults.<br><br>Failure of obliteration of second branchial arch overgrowth creates epithelial-lined cystic cavities.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option C), dermoid cyst (option B), ranula (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) have different embryological origins. Therefore branchial cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with supraglottic carcinoma develops bilateral cervical lymph node metastases early because the supraglottis has:",o:["Poor vascular supply","Thin squamous epithelium","Rich lymphatic drainage","Direct intracranial communication","Extensive venous valves"],a:2,e:"Rich lymphatic drainage fits early bilateral cervical metastasis in supraglottic malignancies. Dysphagia develops clinically commonly.<br><br>The supraglottic region contains abundant communicating lymphatic channels crossing the midline.<br><br>Poor vascular supply (option A), thin squamous epithelium (option B), intracranial communication (option D), and venous valves (option E) are unrelated factors. Therefore rich lymphatics explain metastasis.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops recurrent cystic swelling in lateral neck after incomplete surgery. Histology shows squamous epithelial lining with lymphoid tissue in wall. The diagnosis is:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Sebaceous cyst","Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma"],a:3,e:"Branchial cyst fits cystic lateral neck lesions lined by squamous epithelium with lymphoid aggregates. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>Second branchial cleft remnants commonly demonstrate epithelial lining surrounded by dense lymphoid tissue microscopically.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), sebaceous cyst (option C), and cystic hygroma (option E) show different histological features. Therefore branchial cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neck swelling develops syncope during palpation of carotid bifurcation region. The reflex originates mainly from:",o:["Carotid sinus","Carotid body","Jugular bulb","Vertebral artery","Cavernous sinus"],a:0,e:"Carotid sinus hypersensitivity fits reflex syncope precipitated by neck pressure. Bradycardia develops clinically during stimulation.<br><br>Stretch-sensitive baroreceptors within carotid sinus wall trigger exaggerated vagal cardiovascular responses.<br><br>Carotid body (option B), jugular bulb (option C), vertebral artery (option D), and cavernous sinus (option E) are less directly involved. Therefore carotid sinus mediates the reflex.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A young adult presents with multiple matted cervical lymph nodes and discharging sinus. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Hodgkin lymphoma","Reactive lymphadenopathy","Metastatic squamous carcinoma","Tuberculous lymphadenitis","Lipoma"],a:3,e:"Tuberculous lymphadenitis fits matted cervical nodes with sinus formation. Evening fever develops clinically in chronic disease.<br><br>Granulomatous inflammation with caseous necrosis causes periadenitis and eventual cold abscess rupture through skin.<br><br>Hodgkin lymphoma (option A), reactive lymphadenopathy (option B), metastatic carcinoma (option C), and lipoma (option E) less commonly produce sinus tracts. Therefore tuberculosis is likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with painless enlargement of left supraclavicular node due to gastric carcinoma. The spread occurred mainly through the:",o:["External jugular vein","Thoracic duct","Inferior thyroid vein","Vertebral venous plexus","Superior vena cava"],a:1,e:"Thoracic duct spread fits Virchow node enlargement associated with abdominal malignancy. Advanced disease develops clinically before nodal detection.<br><br>The thoracic duct drains abdominal lymphatic flow into left venous angle near supraclavicular nodes.<br><br>External jugular vein (option A), inferior thyroid vein (option C), vertebral plexus (option D), and superior vena cava (option E) are less important pathways. Therefore thoracic duct is responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with malignant cervical node develops tongue deviation toward affected side. Which nerve has been infiltrated?",o:["Vagus nerve","Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:3,e:"Hypoglossal nerve involvement fits ipsilateral tongue deviation in advanced neck malignancy. Dysarthria develops clinically because of tongue weakness.<br><br>The hypoglossal nerve supplies intrinsic and extrinsic tongue muscles and courses through upper neck near carotid bifurcation.<br><br>Vagus nerve (option A), facial nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option C), and lingual nerve (option E) do not primarily protrude tongue. Therefore hypoglossal nerve is involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with congenital cystic neck swelling lined by respiratory epithelium and attached to hyoid bone. The diagnosis is most likely:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Dermoid cyst","Sebaceous cyst"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cyst fits congenital midline lesions often lined by respiratory epithelium. Infection develops clinically in recurrent cases.<br><br>Persistence of thyroglossal duct remnants during thyroid descent produces epithelial-lined cystic cavities near hyoid region.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option B), cystic hygroma (option C), dermoid cyst (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) differ anatomically and histologically. Therefore thyroglossal cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common primary malignancy metastasizing to cervical lymph nodes is:",o:["Adenocarcinoma","Melanoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Sarcoma","Squamous cell carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits the commonest primary malignancy producing cervical nodal metastasis. Tobacco exposure develops clinically as major risk factor.<br><br>The upper aerodigestive tract is lined predominantly by squamous epithelium susceptible to chronic carcinogenic irritation.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma (option A), melanoma (option B), basal cell carcinoma (option C), and sarcoma (option D) metastasize less frequently to neck nodes. Therefore squamous carcinoma predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops severe chest pain and mediastinitis. The infection most likely spread through the:",o:["Submandibular space","Carotid sheath","Danger space","Pretracheal fascia only","Buccal space"],a:2,e:"Danger space spread fits descending necrotizing mediastinitis from cervical infection. Septic shock develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>This fascial compartment extends uninterrupted from skull base into posterior mediastinum between alar and prevertebral fascia.<br><br>Submandibular space (option A), carotid sheath (option B), pretracheal fascia only (option D), and buccal space (option E) are less direct routes. Therefore danger space is responsible.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A fluctuant lateral neck swelling in a young adult transilluminates poorly and lies deep to platysma. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Lipoma","Sebaceous cyst","Cystic hygroma","Hemangioma"],a:0,e:"Branchial cyst fits a poorly transilluminant fluctuant lateral neck swelling in young adults. Infection develops clinically after recurrent respiratory tract infections.<br><br>Most lesions arise from second branchial cleft remnants deep to platysma near sternocleidomastoid border.<br><br>Lipoma (option B), sebaceous cyst (option C), cystic hygroma (option D), and hemangioma (option E) demonstrate different consistency or transillumination patterns. Therefore branchial cyst is likely.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fixed cervical metastatic nodes and primary oral carcinoma is planned for surgery. The standard operation removing sternocleidomastoid, internal jugular vein, and accessory nerve is:",o:["Functional neck dissection","Selective neck dissection","Supraomohyoid neck dissection","Radical neck dissection","Modified neck dissection"],a:3,e:"Radical neck dissection fits classical en bloc removal of cervical lymphatics with sternocleidomastoid, accessory nerve, and internal jugular vein. Shoulder dysfunction develops clinically afterward.<br><br>This procedure is reserved for extensive metastatic cervical disease involving nonlymphatic structures.<br><br>Functional neck dissection (option A), selective neck dissection (option B), supraomohyoid dissection (option C), and modified dissection (option E) preserve additional structures. Therefore radical neck dissection is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with large neck malignancy develops stridor because of direct compression of the:",o:["Esophagus","Thoracic duct","Internal jugular vein","Trachea","Carotid artery"],a:3,e:"Tracheal compression fits stridor associated with large cervical malignancies. Respiratory distress develops clinically particularly in supine position.<br><br>The trachea lies centrally within visceral compartment and may be narrowed externally by expanding tumors or nodal masses.<br><br>Esophagus (option A), thoracic duct (option B), internal jugular vein (option C), and carotid artery (option E) do not directly cause stridor when compressed. Therefore trachea is involved.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 14-year-old boy presents with a painless midline neck swelling that moves upward during swallowing and protrusion of tongue. The swelling is most likely:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Dermoid cyst","Lipoma"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cyst fits a midline neck swelling moving with tongue protrusion. Recurrent infection develops clinically during adolescence.<br><br>Persistence of thyroglossal tract between foramen cecum and thyroid gland explains characteristic movement during swallowing and tongue motion.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option B), cystic hygroma (option C), dermoid cyst (option D), and lipoma (option E) generally lack this mobility pattern. Therefore thyroglossal cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless cystic swelling located at the upper anterior border of sternocleidomastoid in a young adult is most likely:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Hemangioma","Laryngocele","Sebaceous cyst","Branchial cyst"],a:4,e:"Branchial cyst fits a lateral cystic neck swelling in young adults. Secondary infection develops clinically after upper respiratory tract infections.<br><br>Most branchial cysts arise from second branchial cleft remnants and lie deep to platysma near sternocleidomastoid muscle.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), laryngocele (option C), sebaceous cyst (option D), and hemangioma (option B) occur in different locations. Therefore branchial cyst is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old smoker presents with hard fixed cervical nodes and progressive hoarseness. The most likely pathology is:",o:["Reactive lymphadenopathy","Tuberculous lymphadenitis","Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma","Lipoma","Cystic hygroma"],a:2,e:"Metastatic squamous cell carcinoma fits hard fixed cervical lymph nodes in chronic smokers. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Head and neck squamous cancers spread early through rich cervical lymphatic pathways producing firm infiltrative nodal masses.<br><br>Reactive lymphadenopathy (option A), tuberculous lymphadenitis (option B), lipoma (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) are usually softer lesions. Therefore metastatic carcinoma is likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A pulsatile neck swelling that is mobile horizontally but fixed vertically is characteristic of:",o:["Lipoma","Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Carotid body tumor","Sebaceous cyst"],a:3,e:"Carotid body tumor fits a pulsatile lesion showing side-to-side mobility with restricted vertical movement. Bruit develops clinically over larger masses.<br><br>The tumor arises at carotid bifurcation where attachment to carotid vessels limits superior-inferior displacement.<br><br>Lipoma (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), branchial cyst (option C), and sebaceous cyst (option E) are nonvascular swellings. Therefore carotid body tumor is correct.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops milky drainage after left radical neck dissection. The injured structure is most likely:",o:["Thoracic duct","External jugular vein","Inferior thyroid artery","Internal carotid artery","Recurrent laryngeal nerve"],a:0,e:"Thoracic duct injury fits postoperative chylous fistula after left-sided neck surgery. Nutritional depletion develops clinically if leakage persists.<br><br>The thoracic duct arches into left venous angle near junction of internal jugular and subclavian veins.<br><br>External jugular vein (option B), inferior thyroid artery (option C), internal carotid artery (option D), and recurrent laryngeal nerve (option E) do not transport chyle. Therefore thoracic duct is injured.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with a brilliantly transilluminant multiloculated neck swelling occupying posterior triangle. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Lipoma","Cystic hygroma"],a:4,e:"Cystic hygroma fits a congenital multiloculated transilluminant lesion in posterior triangle. Airway compromise develops clinically in extensive disease.<br><br>Failure of embryological lymphatic sacs to establish venous communication results in diffuse lymph-filled cystic spaces.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option C), and lipoma (option D) do not transilluminate brilliantly. Therefore cystic hygroma is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cervical metastatic nodes develops ipsilateral ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis. Which structure has been infiltrated?",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Accessory nerve","Facial nerve","Lingual nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain"],a:4,e:"Cervical sympathetic chain involvement fits Horner syndrome associated with advanced neck malignancy. Facial flushing develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>The sympathetic trunk lies posterior to carotid sheath and may be compressed by metastatic cervical lymph nodes.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), facial nerve (option C), lingual nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option B) do not produce Horner syndrome. Therefore sympathetic chain is involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A neck swelling enlarges during coughing and contains air on CT imaging. The diagnosis is most likely:",o:["Branchial cyst","Laryngocele","Thyroglossal cyst","Hemangioma","Lipoma"],a:1,e:"Laryngocele fits an air-filled swelling increasing during coughing or Valsalva maneuver. Hoarseness develops clinically in internal lesions.<br><br>Dilatation of laryngeal saccule communicating with laryngeal lumen permits expansion during raised intralaryngeal pressure.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option C), hemangioma (option D), and lipoma (option E) are not air-containing lesions. Therefore laryngocele is correct.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with left supraclavicular nodal enlargement due to gastric carcinoma has involvement of:",o:["Delphian node","Jugulodigastric node","Prelaryngeal node","Virchow node","Submental node"],a:3,e:"Virchow node fits metastatic enlargement of left supraclavicular node from abdominal malignancies. Advanced systemic disease develops clinically before presentation.<br><br>The thoracic duct drains abdominal lymphatic flow into left venous angle near this nodal group.<br><br>Delphian node (option A), jugulodigastric node (option B), prelaryngeal node (option C), and submental node (option E) drain different territories. Therefore Virchow node is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest benign soft tissue tumor of the neck in adults is:",o:["Lipoma","Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Sebaceous cyst","Thyroglossal cyst"],a:0,e:"Lipoma fits the commonest benign soft tissue tumor of adult neck. Slow painless enlargement develops clinically over years.<br><br>Benign proliferation of mature adipocytes enclosed in a thin fibrous capsule produces a soft freely mobile lesion.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option B), cystic hygroma (option C), sebaceous cyst (option D), and thyroglossal cyst (option E) are developmental lesions rather than true tumors. Therefore lipoma is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops shoulder droop and inability to abduct arm after radical neck dissection. The injured nerve is:",o:["Spinal accessory nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:0,e:"Spinal accessory nerve injury fits postoperative shoulder dysfunction following radical neck dissection. Trapezius wasting develops clinically progressively.<br><br>The accessory nerve crosses posterior triangle superficially and remains vulnerable during lymph node clearance procedures.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option B), phrenic nerve (option C), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and lingual nerve (option E) do not primarily supply trapezius. Therefore accessory nerve is injured.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with matted cervical nodes, evening fever, and cold abscess formation most likely has:",o:["Metastatic carcinoma","Reactive lymphadenitis","Branchial cyst","Carotid body tumor","Tuberculous lymphadenitis"],a:4,e:"Tuberculous lymphadenitis fits matted nodes associated with constitutional symptoms and sinus formation. Chronic neck swelling develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Granulomatous inflammation with caseation produces periadenitis leading to nodal adherence and cold abscess formation.<br><br>Metastatic carcinoma (option A), branchial cyst (option C), carotid body tumor (option D), and reactive lymphadenitis (option B) do not typically cause matting with cold abscesses. Therefore tuberculosis is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with large thyroid malignancy develops stridor due to compression of the:",o:["Esophagus","Internal jugular vein","Thoracic duct","Trachea","Carotid artery"],a:3,e:"Tracheal compression fits stridor associated with expanding thyroid malignancies. Respiratory distress develops clinically especially in supine position.<br><br>The thyroid gland surrounds upper trachea closely, allowing large lesions to narrow airway lumen mechanically.<br><br>Esophagus (option A), internal jugular vein (option B), thoracic duct (option C), and carotid artery (option E) do not directly produce stridor. Therefore trachea is compressed.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neck malignancy develops unilateral tongue deviation toward affected side. Which nerve is involved?",o:["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Lingual nerve","Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:4,e:"Hypoglossal nerve involvement fits ipsilateral tongue deviation in advanced cervical disease. Dysarthria develops clinically due to tongue weakness.<br><br>The hypoglossal nerve supplies intrinsic and extrinsic tongue muscles and traverses upper cervical region near carotid arteries.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and vagus nerve (option D) do not protrude tongue. Therefore hypoglossal nerve is involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A recurrent thyroglossal cyst after surgery usually indicates incomplete removal of the:",o:["Thyroid isthmus","Sternohyoid muscle","Submandibular gland","Central part of hyoid bone","Omohyoid tendon"],a:3,e:"Central hyoid bone removal fits the essential principle of Sistrunk operation. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>The thyroglossal tract passes through or closely behind the body of hyoid bone during thyroid descent.<br><br>Thyroid isthmus (option A), sternohyoid muscle (option B), submandibular gland (option C), and omohyoid tendon (option E) are unrelated structures. Therefore central hyoid removal is necessary.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A rapidly enlarging painful cervical swelling with fever and erythematous skin is most suggestive of:",o:["Lipoma","Metastatic node","Branchial cyst","Laryngocele","Acute suppurative lymphadenitis"],a:4,e:"Acute suppurative lymphadenitis fits tender inflamed cervical swelling associated with systemic infection. Fluctuation develops clinically after abscess formation.<br><br>Bacterial invasion of lymph nodes produces edema, neutrophilic infiltration, and localized tissue destruction.<br><br>Lipoma (option A), branchial cyst (option C), laryngocele (option D), and metastatic node (option B) are generally painless initially. Therefore suppurative lymphadenitis is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Early bilateral cervical nodal metastasis in supraglottic carcinoma occurs mainly because of:",o:["Thin epithelium","Rich lymphatic drainage","Venous valve incompetence","Direct skull base communication","Poor vascularity"],a:1,e:"Rich lymphatic drainage fits early bilateral nodal spread in supraglottic malignancies. Dysphagia develops clinically commonly.<br><br>The supraglottis possesses abundant communicating lymphatic channels crossing the midline extensively.<br><br>Thin epithelium (option A), venous valve incompetence (option C), skull base communication (option D), and poor vascularity (option E) are less relevant factors. Therefore rich lymphatics explain metastasis.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The operation involving removal of sternocleidomastoid, internal jugular vein, and accessory nerve is called:",o:["Selective neck dissection","Functional neck dissection","Radical neck dissection","Supraomohyoid dissection","Modified radical dissection"],a:2,e:"Radical neck dissection fits classical removal of cervical lymphatics together with sternocleidomastoid, accessory nerve, and internal jugular vein. Shoulder dysfunction develops clinically afterward.<br><br>This extensive procedure is reserved for advanced metastatic cervical nodal disease involving adjacent structures.<br><br>Selective neck dissection (option A), functional neck dissection (option B), supraomohyoid dissection (option D), and modified radical dissection (option E) preserve more structures. Therefore radical neck dissection is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital torticollis most commonly has fibrosis of:",o:["Trapezius","Platysma","Omohyoid","Sternocleidomastoid","Digastric"],a:3,e:"Sternocleidomastoid fibrosis fits congenital muscular torticollis. Chin deviation develops clinically away from affected side.<br><br>Birth trauma or intrauterine malposition may cause fibrosis and shortening of sternocleidomastoid muscle.<br><br>Trapezius (option A), platysma (option B), omohyoid (option C), and digastric (option E) are less commonly implicated. Therefore sternocleidomastoid is affected.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops mediastinitis due to spread through the:",o:["Carotid sheath","Submandibular space","Pretracheal fascia only","Danger space","Buccal space"],a:3,e:"Danger space spread fits descending necrotizing mediastinitis from cervical infection. Septic shock develops clinically with delayed treatment.<br><br>This fascial compartment extends uninterrupted from skull base into posterior mediastinum between alar and prevertebral fascia.<br><br>Carotid sheath (option A), submandibular space (option B), pretracheal fascia only (option C), and buccal space (option E) are less direct pathways. Therefore danger space is responsible.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old smoker presents with a hard cervical lymph node fixed to underlying structures. Which feature most strongly suggests malignancy rather than inflammatory disease?",o:["Tenderness","Fluctuation","Fixity to surrounding tissues","Warmth of overlying skin","Rapid reduction with antibiotics"],a:2,e:"Fixity to surrounding tissues fits malignant cervical lymphadenopathy. Progressive enlargement develops clinically despite conservative treatment.<br><br>Malignant infiltration extends through nodal capsule into adjacent fascia and muscles, producing immobility on examination.<br><br>Tenderness (option A), fluctuation (option B), warmth (option D), and response to antibiotics (option E) are more suggestive of inflammatory pathology. Therefore fixity strongly favors malignancy.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A congenital cystic neck lesion lined by squamous epithelium with lymphoid tissue in its wall is most likely:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Sebaceous cyst","Branchial cyst","Ranula"],a:3,e:"Branchial cyst fits a lateral cervical lesion lined by squamous epithelium and surrounded by lymphoid tissue. Recurrent infection develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Most arise from remnants of second branchial cleft situated near anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), sebaceous cyst (option C), and ranula (option E) show different histopathological patterns. Therefore branchial cyst is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced hypopharyngeal carcinoma develops aspiration and hoarseness due to involvement of:",o:["Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Great auricular nerve"],a:3,e:"Recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement fits vocal cord paralysis causing aspiration and hoarseness. Airway compromise develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve ascends in tracheoesophageal groove close to hypopharyngeal structures vulnerable to malignant infiltration.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and great auricular nerve (option E) do not directly move vocal cords. Therefore recurrent laryngeal nerve is involved.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A soft compressible neck swelling increasing during Valsalva maneuver is most likely due to:",o:["Venous malformation","Lipoma","Branchial cyst","Sebaceous cyst","Thyroglossal cyst"],a:0,e:"Venous malformation fits a compressible swelling enlarging with raised intrathoracic pressure. Bluish discoloration develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>Valsalva maneuver impedes venous return transiently, leading to distension of abnormal venous channels within lesion.<br><br>Lipoma (option B), branchial cyst (option C), sebaceous cyst (option D), and thyroglossal cyst (option E) do not enlarge significantly with straining. Therefore venous malformation is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with painless enlargement of left supraclavicular node. Which abdominal malignancy classically metastasizes here?",o:["Hepatocellular carcinoma","Gastric carcinoma","Pancreatic insulinoma","Renal angiomyolipoma","Appendiceal carcinoid"],a:1,e:"Gastric carcinoma classically metastasizes to left supraclavicular Virchow node. Weight loss develops clinically before nodal enlargement becomes obvious.<br><br>Abdominal lymphatic drainage reaches thoracic duct which empties near left supraclavicular region.<br><br>Hepatocellular carcinoma (option A), pancreatic insulinoma (option C), renal angiomyolipoma (option D), and appendiceal carcinoid (option E) less commonly present this way. Therefore gastric carcinoma is classic.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with diffuse bilateral submandibular swelling, drooling, fever, and tongue elevation after dental infection. The diagnosis is:",o:["Peritonsillar abscess","Acute parotitis","Ludwig angina","Retropharyngeal abscess","Branchial cyst infection"],a:2,e:"Ludwig angina fits rapidly spreading cellulitis of submandibular and sublingual spaces. Airway obstruction develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Lower molar infections spread through fascial planes producing hard brawny swelling without localized abscess initially.<br><br>Peritonsillar abscess (option A), acute parotitis (option B), retropharyngeal abscess (option D), and branchial cyst infection (option E) differ anatomically and clinically. Therefore Ludwig angina is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common primary source of metastatic cervical lymph nodes in adults is:",o:["Squamous cell carcinoma of upper aerodigestive tract","Basal cell carcinoma of skin","Osteogenic sarcoma","Thyroglossal duct carcinoma","Pituitary adenoma"],a:0,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma fits the commonest primary malignancy metastasizing to cervical lymph nodes. Tobacco exposure develops clinically as major risk factor.<br><br>Upper aerodigestive tract mucosa is lined by squamous epithelium highly susceptible to malignant transformation.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (option B), osteogenic sarcoma (option C), thyroglossal duct carcinoma (option D), and pituitary adenoma (option E) rarely produce cervical nodal spread. Therefore squamous carcinoma predominates.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic neck disease develops inability to shrug shoulder after surgery. Which structure was most likely sacrificed?",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Phrenic nerve","Lingual nerve","Cervical sympathetic chain","Spinal accessory nerve"],a:4,e:"Spinal accessory nerve injury fits postoperative shoulder weakness and drooping after neck dissection. Trapezius wasting develops clinically progressively.<br><br>The accessory nerve crosses posterior triangle superficially and is frequently encountered during cervical nodal surgery.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), phrenic nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and sympathetic chain (option D) do not primarily elevate shoulder. Therefore accessory nerve was sacrificed.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with large neck mass develops inspiratory stridor while lying supine. The symptom most likely results from compression of:",o:["Esophagus","Cervical sympathetic chain","Thoracic duct","Internal jugular vein","Trachea"],a:4,e:"Tracheal compression fits inspiratory stridor caused by large neck masses. Respiratory distress develops clinically particularly in recumbent posture.<br><br>The trachea occupies central visceral compartment and may be narrowed externally by tumors or enlarged lymph nodes.<br><br>Esophagus (option A), thoracic duct (option C), internal jugular vein (option D), and sympathetic chain (option B) do not directly produce stridor. Therefore trachea is compressed.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with congenital muscular torticollis most commonly has fibrosis involving:",o:["Platysma","Digastric muscle","Omohyoid muscle","Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Trapezius muscle"],a:3,e:"Sternocleidomastoid fibrosis fits congenital torticollis presenting with tilted head and rotated chin. Facial asymmetry develops clinically in longstanding cases.<br><br>Birth trauma or intrauterine malposition may produce fibrosis and shortening of sternocleidomastoid muscle fibers.<br><br>Platysma (option A), digastric (option B), omohyoid (option C), and trapezius (option E) are less commonly implicated. Therefore sternocleidomastoid is affected.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A young adult presents with matted cervical lymph nodes, evening fever, and weight loss. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Metastatic squamous carcinoma","Tuberculous lymphadenitis","Lipoma","Branchial cyst","Carotid body tumor"],a:1,e:"Tuberculous lymphadenitis fits matted cervical nodes associated with constitutional symptoms. Cold abscess formation develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Granulomatous inflammation with caseation produces periadenitis causing adherence between affected lymph nodes.<br><br>Metastatic carcinoma (option A), lipoma (option C), branchial cyst (option D), and carotid body tumor (option E) rarely produce matted nodes with evening fever. Therefore tuberculosis is likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A cystic neck swelling enlarging during coughing and communicating with laryngeal lumen is called:",o:["Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst","Laryngocele"],a:4,e:"Laryngocele fits an air-filled cervical swelling enlarging during coughing or Valsalva maneuver. Hoarseness develops clinically in internal lesions.<br><br>Dilatation of laryngeal saccule communicates with laryngeal lumen and expands with raised airway pressure.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option C), dermoid cyst (option D), and cystic hygroma (option B) are not connected to larynx. Therefore laryngocele is correct.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Recurrence after surgery for thyroglossal cyst most commonly results from failure to remove:",o:["Thyroid isthmus","Sternohyoid fascia","Central part of hyoid bone","Strap muscles completely","Submandibular gland"],a:2,e:"Central hyoid bone excision fits the key principle of Sistrunk procedure. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete tract removal.<br><br>The thyroglossal duct passes through or immediately behind the body of hyoid bone during embryological descent.<br><br>Thyroid isthmus (option A), sternohyoid fascia (option B), strap muscles (option D), and submandibular gland (option E) are unrelated structures. Therefore hyoid removal is essential.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hard cervical metastatic nodes develops ipsilateral tongue deviation. Which nerve is involved?",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve","Lingual nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve"],a:3,e:"Hypoglossal nerve involvement fits tongue deviation toward affected side. Dysarthria develops clinically due to tongue muscle weakness.<br><br>The hypoglossal nerve traverses upper cervical region near carotid vessels where metastatic nodes may infiltrate it.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A), facial nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and vagus nerve (option E) do not protrude tongue. Therefore hypoglossal nerve is involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neck abscess develops mediastinitis because infection spread through the:",o:["Submandibular space","Superficial cervical fascia","Carotid sheath only","Buccal space","Danger space"],a:4,e:"Danger space spread fits descending necrotizing mediastinitis from cervical infections. Septic shock develops clinically if untreated.<br><br>This fascial compartment extends uninterrupted from skull base into posterior mediastinum between alar and prevertebral fascia.<br><br>Submandibular space (option A), carotid sheath (option C), buccal space (option D), and superficial fascia (option B) are less direct routes. Therefore danger space is responsible.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A congenital lateral neck cyst arising from remnants of second branchial cleft usually appears along:",o:["Posterior border of trapezius","Midline near hyoid","Anterior border of sternocleidomastoid","Submental region","Floor of mouth"],a:2,e:"Anterior border of sternocleidomastoid fits the classical location of branchial cysts. Infection develops clinically after respiratory illnesses.<br><br>Second branchial cleft remnants persist in upper lateral neck deep to platysma near carotid bifurcation.<br><br>Posterior trapezius border (option A), midline hyoid region (option B), submental region (option D), and floor of mouth (option E) are atypical sites. Therefore anterior sternocleidomastoid border is correct.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with supraglottic carcinoma develops bilateral cervical nodal metastases early because supraglottis possesses:",o:["Rich lymphatic drainage","Thick keratinized epithelium","Extensive venous valves","Minimal vascularity","Direct cranial communication"],a:0,e:"Rich lymphatic drainage fits early bilateral cervical metastases in supraglottic carcinoma. Dysphagia develops clinically commonly.<br><br>The supraglottic region contains abundant communicating lymphatic channels crossing the midline extensively.<br><br>Thick keratinized epithelium (option B), venous valves (option C), minimal vascularity (option D), and cranial communication (option E) are unrelated mechanisms. Therefore rich lymphatics explain spread.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The classical operation removing sternocleidomastoid muscle, accessory nerve, and internal jugular vein is:",o:["Functional neck dissection","Supraomohyoid neck dissection","Selective neck dissection","Modified radical neck dissection","Radical neck dissection"],a:4,e:"Radical neck dissection fits en bloc removal of cervical lymphatics with sternocleidomastoid, internal jugular vein, and accessory nerve. Shoulder dysfunction develops clinically postoperatively.<br><br>This extensive procedure is reserved for advanced metastatic cervical disease involving surrounding structures.<br><br>Functional dissection (option A), supraomohyoid dissection (option B), selective dissection (option C), and modified radical dissection (option D) preserve one or more structures. Therefore radical neck dissection is correct.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A brilliantly transilluminant multiloculated neck swelling crossing fascial planes is most likely:",o:["Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Lipoma","Cystic hygroma","Sebaceous cyst"],a:3,e:"Cystic hygroma fits a transilluminant multiloculated lesion infiltrating multiple fascial planes. Airway compromise develops clinically in extensive cases.<br><br>Congenital lymphatic malformations form interconnected endothelial-lined cystic spaces containing lymphatic fluid.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option B), lipoma (option C), and sebaceous cyst (option E) are usually localized lesions. Therefore cystic hygroma is likely.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops postoperative chylous fistula after left neck dissection. The injured structure normally drains into the junction of:",o:["External jugular and subclavian veins","Internal jugular and subclavian veins","Vertebral and brachiocephalic veins","Facial and lingual veins","Common carotid and jugular veins"],a:1,e:"Thoracic duct injury fits postoperative chylous fistula after left neck surgery. Nutritional and electrolyte disturbances develop clinically with persistent leakage.<br><br>The thoracic duct arches across root of neck before entering left venous angle between internal jugular and subclavian veins.<br><br>External jugular and subclavian veins (option A), vertebral and brachiocephalic veins (option C), facial and lingual veins (option D), and carotid-jugular junction (option E) are incorrect sites. Therefore left venous angle is correct.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old smoker presents with a hard level II cervical lymph node and persistent unilateral otalgia without ear pathology. The occult primary should first be suspected in the:",o:["Oropharynx","Nasopharynx","Hypopharynx","Oral tongue","Thyroid gland"],a:0,e:"Oropharyngeal malignancy fits referred otalgia with upper deep cervical lymphadenopathy in smokers. Dysphagia develops clinically in progressive disease.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve sensory pathways commonly produce referred ear pain from tonsillar and oropharyngeal lesions.<br><br>Nasopharynx (option B), hypopharynx (option C), oral tongue (option D), and thyroid gland (option E) are less classically associated with this presentation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A congenital cystic lesion lying deep to platysma near anterior border of sternocleidomastoid most likely arises from:",o:["Thyroglossal duct","First branchial pouch","Tuberculous sinus","Second branchial cleft","Cervical sympathetic chain"],a:3,e:"Second branchial cleft anomalies fit the commonest congenital lateral neck cysts. Recurrent infection develops clinically after upper respiratory illnesses.<br><br>Embryological persistence of cervical sinus remnants produces epithelial-lined cystic swellings in lateral neck.<br><br>Thyroglossal duct (option A), first branchial pouch (option B), tuberculous sinus (option C), and sympathetic chain lesions (option E) produce different pathologies.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic neck disease develops severe wasting of trapezius after surgery. Which movement becomes most impaired?",o:["Tongue protrusion","Shoulder elevation","Elbow flexion","Wrist extension","Jaw opening"],a:1,e:"Shoulder elevation impairment fits trapezius paralysis after accessory nerve sacrifice. Shoulder drooping develops clinically prominently.<br><br>The spinal accessory nerve supplies trapezius muscle responsible for scapular stabilization and shoulder shrugging.<br><br>Tongue protrusion (option A), elbow flexion (option C), wrist extension (option D), and jaw opening (option E) depend on different nerves and muscles.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with a painless soft mobile neck swelling that slips beneath examining fingers. The diagnosis is most likely:",o:["Branchial cyst","Metastatic node","Sebaceous cyst","Lipoma","Carotid body tumor"],a:3,e:"Lipoma fits a soft mobile swelling demonstrating classical slip sign. Cosmetic concern develops clinically more commonly than pain.<br><br>Benign proliferation of mature adipocytes enclosed within a thin capsule creates characteristic doughy consistency.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), metastatic node (option B), sebaceous cyst (option C), and carotid body tumor (option E) are less freely mobile.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops chylous fistula after left radical neck dissection. The injured structure normally terminates at the junction of:",o:["External jugular and subclavian veins","Common carotid and jugular veins","Facial and lingual veins","Vertebral and brachiocephalic veins","Internal jugular and subclavian veins"],a:4,e:"Thoracic duct injury fits postoperative chylous fistula after left neck surgery. Electrolyte imbalance develops clinically with persistent leakage.<br><br>The thoracic duct arches in the root of neck before entering the left venous angle.<br><br>External jugular and subclavian veins (option A), facial and lingual veins (option C), vertebral and brachiocephalic veins (option D), and carotid-jugular junction (option B) are incorrect sites.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 6-year-old child presents with diffuse bilateral submandibular swelling, drooling, and tongue elevation after molar tooth infection. The diagnosis is:",o:["Acute parotitis","Branchial cyst infection","Retropharyngeal abscess","Peritonsillar abscess","Ludwig angina"],a:4,e:"Ludwig angina fits rapidly spreading cellulitis involving submandibular and sublingual spaces. Airway compromise develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Odontogenic infections spread through fascial planes producing tense brawny swelling of floor of mouth.<br><br>Acute parotitis (option A), retropharyngeal abscess (option C), peritonsillar abscess (option D), and branchial cyst infection (option B) involve different compartments.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with fixed cervical metastatic nodes develops ipsilateral tongue deviation. Which cranial nerve is infiltrated?",o:["Facial nerve","Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:2,e:"Hypoglossal nerve involvement fits tongue deviation toward affected side. Dysarthria develops clinically due to tongue weakness.<br><br>The nerve traverses upper cervical region close to carotid bifurcation where metastatic nodes may infiltrate it.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and lingual nerve (option E) do not protrude tongue.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A cystic neck swelling enlarges during coughing and decreases at rest. CT reveals communication with laryngeal ventricle. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Laryngocele","Hemangioma"],a:3,e:"Laryngocele fits an air-filled swelling increasing during coughing or Valsalva maneuver. Hoarseness develops clinically in internal lesions.<br><br>Dilatation of laryngeal saccule communicating with laryngeal lumen explains intermittent enlargement.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option C), and hemangioma (option E) are not connected to laryngeal cavity.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with supraglottic carcinoma develops early bilateral cervical metastases mainly because supraglottis has:",o:["Poor blood supply","Rich lymphatic drainage","Thick squamous epithelium","Extensive venous valves","Minimal fascial support"],a:1,e:"Rich lymphatic drainage explains early bilateral cervical nodal spread in supraglottic cancers. Dysphagia develops clinically commonly.<br><br>The supraglottic region contains abundant lymphatic channels crossing the midline extensively.<br><br>Poor blood supply (option A), thick epithelium (option C), venous valves (option D), and fascial support (option E) are less relevant.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A recurrent thyroglossal cyst after previous surgery usually indicates failure to remove the:",o:["Thyroid isthmus","Strap muscles","Central hyoid bone segment","Submandibular gland","Carotid sheath fascia"],a:2,e:"Central hyoid excision forms the key step of Sistrunk operation. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete tract removal.<br><br>The thyroglossal duct passes through or immediately behind the body of hyoid bone embryologically.<br><br>Thyroid isthmus (option A), strap muscles (option B), submandibular gland (option D), and carotid fascia (option E) are less relevant.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops mediastinitis through spread in the:",o:["Carotid sheath","Buccal space","Submandibular space","Danger space","Superficial fascia"],a:3,e:"Danger space spread fits descending necrotizing mediastinitis from cervical infection. Septic shock develops clinically with delayed treatment.<br><br>This fascial compartment extends uninterrupted from skull base into posterior mediastinum.<br><br>Carotid sheath (option A), buccal space (option B), submandibular space (option C), and superficial fascia (option E) are less direct pathways.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 20-year-old woman presents with a brilliantly transilluminant multiloculated swelling occupying posterior triangle. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Lipoma","Sebaceous cyst","Metastatic node"],a:1,e:"Cystic hygroma fits a multiloculated transilluminant lesion crossing fascial planes. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in large lesions.<br><br>Congenital lymphatic malformations form interconnected endothelial-lined cystic spaces containing lymphatic fluid.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), lipoma (option C), sebaceous cyst (option D), and metastatic node (option E) are less transilluminant.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with metastatic cervical nodes presents with ptosis, miosis, and facial anhidrosis. Which structure is affected?",o:["Cervical sympathetic chain","Vagus nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Facial nerve"],a:0,e:"Cervical sympathetic chain involvement fits Horner syndrome in advanced neck malignancy. Facial flushing develops clinically occasionally.<br><br>The sympathetic trunk lies posterior to carotid sheath and may be infiltrated by metastatic nodes.<br><br>Vagus nerve (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option C), lingual nerve (option D), and facial nerve (option E) do not produce Horner syndrome.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A hard left supraclavicular node associated with gastric carcinoma is known as:",o:["Delphian node","Jugulodigastric node","Virchow node","Jugulo-omohyoid node","Submental node"],a:2,e:"Virchow node fits metastatic enlargement of left supraclavicular node from abdominal malignancy. Weight loss develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Abdominal lymphatic drainage enters thoracic duct before reaching left supraclavicular region.<br><br>Delphian node (option A), jugulodigastric node (option B), jugulo-omohyoid node (option D), and submental node (option E) drain different regions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant neck mass in adults is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Lipoma","Metastatic lymph node","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma"],a:2,e:"Metastatic lymph node fits the commonest malignant cervical swelling in adults. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Upper aerodigestive tract malignancies commonly spread through rich cervical lymphatic networks.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), lipoma (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) are benign lesions.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe shoulder drooping after radical neck dissection because of injury to the:",o:["Phrenic nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Spinal accessory nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:3,e:"Spinal accessory nerve injury fits postoperative shoulder drooping and impaired arm abduction. Trapezius wasting develops clinically progressively.<br><br>The accessory nerve crosses posterior triangle superficially and remains vulnerable during neck dissection.<br><br>Phrenic nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), vagus nerve (option C), and lingual nerve (option E) have different functions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with matted cervical nodes and cold abscess formation most likely has:",o:["Reactive lymphadenitis","Carotid body tumor","Branchial cyst","Metastatic carcinoma","Tuberculous lymphadenitis"],a:4,e:"Tuberculous lymphadenitis fits matted nodes associated with cold abscesses and constitutional symptoms. Sinus formation develops clinically in chronic disease.<br><br>Granulomatous inflammation with caseation causes periadenitis leading to nodal adherence.<br><br>Reactive lymphadenitis (option A), branchial cyst (option C), metastatic carcinoma (option D), and carotid body tumor (option B) usually do not produce matted nodes with cold abscesses.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with a large thyroid malignancy develops inspiratory stridor because of compression of the:",o:["Esophagus","Internal jugular vein","Trachea","Thoracic duct","Common carotid artery"],a:2,e:"Tracheal compression fits inspiratory stridor associated with expanding thyroid malignancy. Respiratory distress develops clinically in supine posture.<br><br>The thyroid gland lies closely related to upper trachea and may narrow airway lumen mechanically.<br><br>Esophagus (option A), internal jugular vein (option B), thoracic duct (option D), and carotid artery (option E) do not directly cause stridor.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The classical operation removing sternocleidomastoid, accessory nerve, and internal jugular vein is:",o:["Functional neck dissection","Radical neck dissection","Selective neck dissection","Supraomohyoid dissection","Modified radical dissection"],a:1,e:"Radical neck dissection fits en bloc removal of cervical lymphatics with sternocleidomastoid muscle, accessory nerve, and internal jugular vein. Shoulder dysfunction develops clinically afterward.<br><br>This extensive procedure is reserved for advanced metastatic cervical disease.<br><br>Functional dissection (option A), selective dissection (option C), supraomohyoid dissection (option D), and modified radical dissection (option E) preserve one or more structures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A congenital lateral neck swelling anterior to sternocleidomastoid usually becomes apparent during:",o:["Neonatal period only","Immediately after birth in all cases","Late old age","Intrauterine life only","Adolescence or early adulthood"],a:4,e:"Branchial cysts commonly present during adolescence or early adulthood despite congenital origin. Infection develops clinically after respiratory illnesses.<br><br>Gradual enlargement occurs because epithelial remnants accumulate secretions over time.<br><br>Neonatal period only (option A), late old age (option C), intrauterine life only (option D), and immediate birth presentation in all cases (option B) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with a neck swelling showing \"slip sign\" most likely has:",o:["Branchial cyst","Carotid body tumor","Metastatic node","Sebaceous cyst","Lipoma"],a:4,e:"Lipoma fits a soft mobile swelling demonstrating characteristic slip sign during palpation. Cosmetic deformity develops clinically gradually.<br><br>Benign adipose tissue enclosed in a thin capsule creates a doughy freely mobile lesion.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), metastatic node (option C), sebaceous cyst (option D), and carotid body tumor (option B) are less mobile.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with carcinoma tongue develops enlargement of the node located near posterior belly of digastric and internal jugular vein. The involved node is:",o:["Jugulo-omohyoid node","Virchow node","Delphian node","Jugulodigastric node","Submental node"],a:3,e:"Jugulodigastric node fits upper deep cervical nodal enlargement from oral cavity malignancies. Dysphagia develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>This node lies beneath sternocleidomastoid near posterior belly of digastric muscle.<br><br>Jugulo-omohyoid node (option A), Virchow node (option B), Delphian node (option C), and submental node (option E) drain different territories.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops recurrent cervical swelling after incomplete excision of branchial cyst because the tract often passes between:",o:["External and internal carotid arteries","Common carotid artery and jugular vein","Facial artery and lingual artery","Vertebral artery and subclavian vein","External jugular vein and sternocleidomastoid"],a:0,e:"Second branchial fistulous tracts classically pass between internal and external carotid arteries. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>Close anatomical relations make surgery technically demanding in extensive branchial anomalies.<br><br>Common carotid-jugular relation (option B), facial-lingual arteries (option C), vertebral-subclavian vessels (option D), and external jugular-sternocleidomastoid relation (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced cervical metastasis develops inability to abduct arm above shoulder level. The paralyzed muscle is:",o:["Sternocleidomastoid","Deltoid","Trapezius","Supraspinatus","Rhomboid major"],a:2,e:"Trapezius paralysis fits inability to abduct arm above shoulder level after accessory nerve injury. Shoulder drooping develops clinically prominently.<br><br>The trapezius stabilizes scapula during upper limb abduction.<br><br>Sternocleidomastoid (option A), deltoid (option B), supraspinatus (option D), and rhomboid major (option E) perform different primary actions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with posterior triangle swelling that brilliantly transilluminates and crosses fascial planes most likely has:",o:["Branchial cyst","Lipoma","Metastatic node","Sebaceous cyst","Cystic hygroma"],a:4,e:"Cystic hygroma fits a transilluminant multiloculated lesion extending across tissue planes. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>Congenital lymphatic malformations create diffuse interconnected cystic spaces filled with lymphatic fluid.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), lipoma (option B), sebaceous cyst (option D), and metastatic node (option C) are more localized lesions.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest congenital cyst of the neck is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Dermoid cyst","Sebaceous cyst"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cyst is described in Dhingra as the commonest congenital cyst of the neck. Infection develops clinically frequently during childhood.<br><br>It arises from persistence of the thyroglossal tract during descent of thyroid gland from foramen cecum.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option B), cystic hygroma (option C), dermoid cyst (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) are less common congenital neck cysts.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst classically moves with:",o:["Respiration only","Swallowing only","Tongue protrusion only","Swallowing and tongue protrusion","Valsalva maneuver only"],a:3,e:"Movement with swallowing and tongue protrusion is a classical feature emphasized in Dhingra for thyroglossal cysts. Infection develops clinically recurrently.<br><br>The tract remains attached to foramen cecum through fibrous tissue related to hyoid bone.<br><br>Respiration only (option A), swallowing only (option B), tongue protrusion only (option C), and Valsalva maneuver only (option E) are incomplete descriptions.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest branchial anomaly is:",o:["First branchial cleft cyst","Third branchial fistula","Second branchial cyst","Fourth branchial sinus","Cervical thymic cyst"],a:2,e:"Second branchial cyst is the commonest branchial anomaly according to Dhingra. Painless lateral neck swelling develops clinically in young adults.<br><br>It arises from persistence of the cervical sinus formed during development of second branchial arch.<br><br>First branchial cleft cyst (option A), third branchial fistula (option B), fourth branchial sinus (option D), and cervical thymic cyst (option E) are less common.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A branchial cyst is usually situated along the:",o:["Posterior border of trapezius","Midline near hyoid bone","Lower border of mandible","Anterior border of sternocleidomastoid","Posterior pharyngeal wall"],a:3,e:"Anterior border of sternocleidomastoid is the classical location described in Dhingra for branchial cysts. Infection develops clinically after upper respiratory tract infections.<br><br>Most lesions occur in upper part of neck near carotid bifurcation.<br><br>Posterior trapezius border (option A), midline hyoid region (option B), lower mandible (option C), and posterior pharyngeal wall (option E) are atypical.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The treatment of thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Incision and drainage","Marsupialization","Aspiration only","Radiotherapy","Sistrunk operation"],a:4,e:"Sistrunk operation is the standard treatment emphasized in Dhingra for thyroglossal cysts. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>The procedure includes removal of cyst, tract, and central part of hyoid bone.<br><br>Incision and drainage (option A), marsupialization (option B), aspiration (option C), and radiotherapy (option D) are inadequate definitive treatments.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest cause of lateral neck swelling in an adult should be considered:",o:["Congenital lesion","Tuberculosis","Metastatic malignancy","Lipoma","Lymphangioma"],a:2,e:"Dhingra emphasizes that a lateral neck swelling in adults should be considered metastatic until proved otherwise. Weight loss develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Upper aerodigestive tract cancers commonly metastasize to cervical lymph nodes.<br><br>Congenital lesion (option A), tuberculosis (option B), lipoma (option D), and lymphangioma (option E) are less likely in older adults.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of cystic hygroma is the:",o:["Submental region","Posterior triangle","Parotid region","Submandibular region","Midline neck"],a:1,e:"Posterior triangle is the commonest site of cystic hygroma according to Dhingra. Respiratory difficulty develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>These congenital lymphatic malformations often infiltrate fascial planes diffusely.<br><br>Submental region (option A), parotid region (option C), submandibular region (option D), and midline neck (option E) are less common sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A laryngocele enlarges on:",o:["Tongue protrusion","Swallowing","Jaw opening","Neck flexion","Valsalva maneuver"],a:4,e:"Laryngocele classically enlarges during Valsalva maneuver as described in Dhingra. Hoarseness develops clinically in internal lesions.<br><br>The lesion communicates with laryngeal lumen and fills with air when intralaryngeal pressure rises.<br><br>Tongue protrusion (option A), swallowing (option B), neck flexion (option D), and jaw opening (option C) do not characteristically enlarge laryngoceles.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Ludwig angina involves the:",o:["Retropharyngeal space","Parapharyngeal space","Buccal space","Sublingual and submandibular spaces","Prevertebral space"],a:3,e:"Dhingra describes Ludwig angina as cellulitis involving submandibular and sublingual spaces bilaterally. Airway obstruction develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Dental infections of lower molars are common initiating factors.<br><br>Retropharyngeal space (option A), parapharyngeal space (option B), buccal space (option C), and prevertebral space (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common presentation of metastatic neck disease is enlargement of:",o:["Submental nodes","Occipital nodes","Deep cervical nodes","Postauricular nodes","Buccal nodes"],a:2,e:"Deep cervical node enlargement is the commonest presentation of metastatic neck disease according to Dhingra. Progressive nodal enlargement develops clinically commonly.<br><br>These nodes receive lymphatic drainage from most upper aerodigestive tract structures.<br><br>Submental nodes (option A), occipital nodes (option B), postauricular nodes (option D), and buccal nodes (option E) are less commonly involved initially.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest cause of congenital muscular torticollis is fibrosis of:",o:["Platysma","Digastric muscle","Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Trapezius muscle","Omohyoid muscle"],a:2,e:"Fibrosis of sternocleidomastoid muscle is the classical lesion in congenital muscular torticollis described in Dhingra. Facial asymmetry develops clinically in longstanding cases.<br><br>Birth trauma and ischemic injury are proposed etiological mechanisms.<br><br>Platysma (option A), digastric (option B), trapezius (option D), and omohyoid (option E) are less commonly implicated.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important complication of Ludwig angina is:",o:["Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Facial nerve palsy","Airway obstruction","Meningitis","Hearing loss"],a:2,e:"Airway obstruction is emphasized in Dhingra as the most dangerous complication of Ludwig angina. Tongue elevation develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Diffuse cellulitis displaces the tongue posteriorly and narrows upper airway.<br><br>Cavernous sinus thrombosis (option A), facial nerve palsy (option B), meningitis (option D), and hearing loss (option E) are less immediate complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A branchial fistula usually opens externally at the:",o:["Midline neck","Lower border of mandible","Suprasternal notch","Posterior triangle apex","Anterior border of sternocleidomastoid"],a:4,e:"Dhingra describes the external opening of branchial fistula near anterior border of sternocleidomastoid in lower neck. Mucoid discharge develops clinically recurrently.<br><br>Most fistulous tracts arise from second branchial cleft anomalies.<br><br>Midline neck (option A), lower mandible (option B), posterior triangle apex (option D), and suprasternal notch (option C) are uncommon sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The treatment of branchial cyst is:",o:["Aspiration only","Incision and drainage only","Chemotherapy","Complete surgical excision","Radiotherapy"],a:3,e:"Complete surgical excision is the recommended treatment for branchial cysts in Dhingra. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete removal.<br><br>The tract should be carefully dissected because of proximity to carotid vessels.<br><br>Aspiration (option A), incision and drainage (option B), chemotherapy (option C), and radiotherapy (option E) are inadequate definitive treatments.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest organism causing Ludwig angina is:",o:["Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Candida albicans","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Corynebacterium diphtheriae","Mixed streptococcal infection"],a:4,e:"Mixed streptococcal infection is classically implicated in Ludwig angina according to Dhingra. Fever and toxic appearance develop clinically prominently.<br><br>Anaerobes and oral cavity flora often contribute to polymicrobial infection.<br><br>Pseudomonas (option A), tuberculosis (option C), diphtheria (option D), and Candida (option B) are less typical pathogens.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest congenital lateral neck cyst is:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Ranula","Thyroglossal cyst","Sebaceous cyst","Branchial cyst"],a:4,e:"Branchial cyst is described in Dhingra as the commonest congenital lateral neck cyst. Painless swelling develops clinically in young adults.<br><br>Most lesions arise from remnants of second branchial cleft.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option C), sebaceous cyst (option D), and ranula (option B) are less common lateral cysts.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst is usually located:",o:["Along anterior border of sternocleidomastoid","In posterior triangle","In the midline","In parotid region","Behind angle of mandible"],a:2,e:"Midline location is a classical feature of thyroglossal cyst emphasized in Dhingra. Infection develops clinically recurrently.<br><br>The lesion follows the embryological descent pathway of thyroid gland.<br><br>Anterior sternocleidomastoid border (option A), posterior triangle (option B), parotid region (option D), and mandibular angle (option E) are atypical sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common symptom of laryngocele is:",o:["Dysphagia","Hoarseness","Facial pain","Epistaxis","Hearing loss"],a:1,e:"Hoarseness is the commonest symptom of laryngocele described in Dhingra. Neck swelling develops clinically in external lesions.<br><br>Internal laryngoceles interfere with normal vibration and function of supraglottic structures.<br><br>Dysphagia (option A), facial pain (option C), epistaxis (option D), and hearing loss (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred imaging investigation for cystic hygroma is:",o:["Plain X-ray neck","Ultrasonography","MRI","Sialography","Barium swallow"],a:2,e:"MRI is emphasized in Dhingra for defining extent of cystic hygroma. Airway compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>The lesion commonly infiltrates fascial planes and requires detailed soft tissue delineation.<br><br>Plain X-ray (option A), ultrasonography (option B), sialography (option D), and barium swallow (option E) provide less anatomical detail.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cause of acquired torticollis in children is:",o:["Sternocleidomastoid fibrosis","Cervical spine fracture","Retropharyngeal abscess","Thyroid malignancy","Carotid aneurysm"],a:2,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess is a common acquired cause of torticollis in children according to Dhingra. Dysphagia develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Pain and muscle spasm produce abnormal neck posture.<br><br>Sternocleidomastoid fibrosis (option A), cervical fracture (option B), thyroid malignancy (option D), and carotid aneurysm (option E) are less common acquired causes.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A cystic hygroma arises from malformation of the:",o:["Salivary glands","Branchial arches","Neural crest","Thyroid gland","Lymphatic system"],a:4,e:"Cystic hygroma is described as a congenital malformation of lymphatic system in Dhingra. Progressive enlargement develops clinically during childhood.<br><br>Failure of lymph sacs to establish normal venous communication produces multiloculated cystic spaces.<br><br>Salivary glands (option A), branchial arches (option B), thyroid gland (option D), and neural crest (option C) are unrelated origins.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The external opening of a complete branchial fistula is usually found in the:",o:["Upper neck","Postauricular region","Midline neck","Submental region","Lower one-third of neck"],a:4,e:"Dhingra describes the external opening of complete branchial fistula in lower one-third of neck near sternocleidomastoid. Mucoid discharge develops clinically recurrently.<br><br>The tract often communicates internally with tonsillar fossa.<br><br>Upper neck (option A), midline neck (option C), submental region (option D), and postauricular region (option B) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common primary site causing metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy is:",o:["Thyroid gland","Upper aerodigestive tract","Orbit","Salivary gland","Skin appendages"],a:1,e:"Upper aerodigestive tract malignancies are the commonest source of metastatic cervical nodes according to Dhingra. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Rich lymphatic drainage facilitates spread to deep cervical lymph nodes.<br><br>Thyroid gland (option A), orbit (option C), salivary gland (option D), and skin appendages (option E) are less common sources.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The danger space of neck extends from skull base to the:",o:["Clavicle","Carina","Posterior mediastinum","Sternum","Thyroid cartilage"],a:2,e:"Dhingra emphasizes that danger space extends into posterior mediastinum allowing rapid spread of infection. Septic complications develop clinically rapidly.<br><br>Descending necrotizing mediastinitis may occur from deep neck infections.<br><br>Clavicle (option A), carina (option B), sternum (option D), and thyroid cartilage (option E) are incomplete limits.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest presentation of branchial cyst is:",o:["Painful swelling in infancy","Air-filled neck swelling","Midline swelling in elderly","Pulsatile neck mass","Painless fluctuant swelling in young adults"],a:4,e:"Dhingra describes branchial cyst classically as painless fluctuant swelling in young adults. Infection develops clinically after respiratory illnesses.<br><br>The lesion enlarges slowly due to accumulation of epithelial secretions.<br><br>Painful infant swelling (option A), midline elderly swelling (option C), pulsatile mass (option D), and air-filled swelling (option B) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of internal opening of a second branchial fistula is:",o:["Pyriform fossa","Nasopharynx","Tonsillar fossa","Vallecula","Floor of mouth"],a:2,e:"Dhingra describes the internal opening of a complete second branchial fistula near the tonsillar fossa. Recurrent mucoid discharge develops clinically from the external opening.<br><br>The tract passes between internal and external carotid arteries before reaching the tonsillar region embryologically.<br><br>Pyriform fossa (option A), nasopharynx (option B), vallecula (option D), and floor of mouth (option E) are less typical sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest presentation of thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Painful neck abscess","Fixed malignant node","Pulsatile neck swelling","Air-filled swelling","Midline cystic neck swelling"],a:4,e:"Midline cystic neck swelling is the classical presentation of thyroglossal cyst described in Dhingra. Infection develops clinically after recurrent upper respiratory infections.<br><br>The lesion usually appears close to the hyoid bone along the embryological descent tract of thyroid gland.<br><br>Painful abscess (option A), pulsatile swelling (option C), air-filled swelling (option D), and fixed malignant node (option B) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous complication of deep neck space infection is:",o:["Facial paralysis","Hearing loss","Glossitis","Cataract formation","Mediastinitis"],a:4,e:"Mediastinitis is emphasized in Dhingra as the most serious complication of deep neck infections. Septic shock develops clinically rapidly with delayed treatment.<br><br>Infection spreads through fascial planes, especially the danger space extending into posterior mediastinum.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), hearing loss (option B), cataract formation (option D), and glossitis (option C) are less significant complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst commonly lies:",o:["Lateral to sternocleidomastoid","In posterior triangle","In supraclavicular fossa","Close to hyoid bone","Near parotid gland"],a:3,e:"Dhingra describes thyroglossal cyst as usually lying near the hyoid bone in the midline. Upward movement occurs clinically during tongue protrusion.<br><br>The thyroglossal tract passes through or behind the central part of hyoid bone embryologically.<br><br>Lateral sternocleidomastoid region (option A), posterior triangle (option B), supraclavicular fossa (option C), and parotid region (option E) are atypical locations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common age group affected by branchial cyst is:",o:["Neonates","Young adults","Elderly patients","Infants only","Preschool children"],a:1,e:"Branchial cyst commonly presents in young adults according to Dhingra. Infection develops clinically after upper respiratory tract infections.<br><br>Congenital epithelial remnants enlarge slowly over years before becoming clinically apparent.<br><br>Neonates (option A), elderly patients (option C), infants (option D), and preschool children (option E) are less commonly affected.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest cause of Ludwig angina is infection of:",o:["Upper molar teeth","Salivary glands","Tonsils","Nasopharynx","Lower molar teeth"],a:4,e:"Lower molar tooth infection is the commonest cause of Ludwig angina emphasized in Dhingra. Fever and toxic appearance develop clinically prominently.<br><br>Roots of lower molars extend below mylohyoid attachment allowing spread into submandibular spaces.<br><br>Upper molars (option A), tonsils (option C), nasopharynx (option D), and salivary glands (option B) are less common sources.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common symptom produced by metastatic cervical lymph nodes is:",o:["Facial paralysis","Diplopia","Hearing loss","Trismus","Neck swelling"],a:4,e:"Neck swelling is the commonest presentation of metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy according to Dhingra. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Deep cervical lymph nodes enlarge because of metastasis from upper aerodigestive tract malignancies.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), hearing loss (option C), trismus (option D), and diplopia (option B) are less frequent presenting features.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest congenital lesion presenting in posterior triangle is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma","Dermoid cyst","Ranula"],a:2,e:"Cystic hygroma commonly presents in posterior triangle according to Dhingra. Respiratory difficulty develops clinically in large infiltrative lesions.<br><br>The lesion represents congenital malformation of lymphatic channels forming multiloculated cystic spaces.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and ranula (option E) usually occur elsewhere.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for confirming cystic nature of neck swelling is:",o:["Audiometry","CT angiography","Ultrasonography","ECG","Plain skull X-ray"],a:2,e:"Ultrasonography is emphasized in Dhingra for evaluating cystic neck lesions. Fluid-filled cavities develop clinically as fluctuant swellings.<br><br>The investigation differentiates solid from cystic masses and helps guide further management.<br><br>Audiometry (option A), CT angiography (option B), ECG (option D), and skull X-ray (option E) are less appropriate initial investigations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common organism isolated in deep neck infections is:",o:["Candida albicans","Streptococci","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Clostridium tetani"],a:1,e:"Streptococci are commonly implicated in deep neck infections according to Dhingra. Fever and severe odynophagia develop clinically frequently.<br><br>Mixed aerobic and anaerobic flora from oral cavity often participate in infection spread.<br><br>Candida (option A), tuberculosis (option C), Pseudomonas (option D), and Clostridium tetani (option E) are less typical organisms.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common symptom of thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Neck swelling","Hoarseness","Trismus","Facial pain","Epistaxis"],a:0,e:"Neck swelling is the commonest presenting complaint of thyroglossal cyst according to Dhingra. Recurrent infection develops clinically in longstanding lesions.<br><br>The swelling usually lies in midline and moves with swallowing and tongue protrusion.<br><br>Hoarseness (option B), trismus (option C), facial pain (option D), and epistaxis (option E) are uncommon presentations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred treatment for cystic hygroma is:",o:["Radiotherapy","Tonsillectomy","Chemotherapy","Aspiration only","Complete surgical excision"],a:4,e:"Complete surgical excision is the preferred treatment for cystic hygroma described in Dhingra. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete removal.<br><br>The lesion often infiltrates fascial planes making surgery technically difficult in extensive disease.<br><br>Radiotherapy (option A), chemotherapy (option C), aspiration (option D), and tonsillectomy (option B) are not definitive treatments.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A branchial cyst usually contains:",o:["Clear cerebrospinal fluid","Thick cheesy material","Salivary secretions","Blood clots only","Straw-colored fluid with cholesterol crystals"],a:4,e:"Dhingra describes branchial cyst fluid as straw colored and containing cholesterol crystals. Painless fluctuant swelling develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Desquamated epithelial debris accumulates gradually within the cyst cavity over years.<br><br>Cerebrospinal fluid (option A), cheesy material (option B), blood clots (option D), and salivary secretions (option C) are less characteristic contents.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site of external opening of branchial fistula is:",o:["Midline neck","Upper border of thyroid cartilage","Lower one-third of neck","Posterior triangle apex","Mastoid region"],a:2,e:"The external opening of branchial fistula usually lies in lower one-third of neck according to Dhingra. Mucoid discharge develops clinically intermittently.<br><br>The opening is typically situated near anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle.<br><br>Midline neck (option A), thyroid cartilage level (option B), posterior triangle apex (option D), and mastoid region (option E) are atypical sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common source of cervical nodal metastasis is carcinoma of the:",o:["Upper aerodigestive tract","Orbit","External ear","Salivary gland duct","Thyroid cartilage"],a:0,e:"Upper aerodigestive tract carcinoma is the commonest source of cervical nodal metastasis according to Dhingra. Progressive neck swelling develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Rich lymphatic drainage facilitates spread to deep cervical lymph nodes.<br><br>Orbit (option B), external ear (option C), salivary duct (option D), and thyroid cartilage (option E) contribute less commonly.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest symptom of Ludwig angina is:",o:["Epistaxis","Dysphagia","Otorrhea","Diplopia","Vertigo"],a:1,e:"Dysphagia is a frequent symptom in Ludwig angina according to Dhingra. Tongue elevation develops clinically because of sublingual space involvement.<br><br>Diffuse cellulitis of floor of mouth interferes with swallowing and airway patency.<br><br>Epistaxis (option A), otorrhea (option C), diplopia (option D), and vertigo (option E) are unrelated symptoms.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest deep neck space infection in children is:",o:["Parapharyngeal abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Bezold abscess","Buccal abscess","Temporal space abscess"],a:1,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess is common in children according to Dhingra. Fever and neck stiffness develop clinically prominently.<br><br>Retropharyngeal lymph nodes are prominent in children and regress later in life.<br><br>Parapharyngeal abscess (option A), Bezold abscess (option C), buccal abscess (option D), and temporal space abscess (option E) occur less commonly.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The classical sign of thyroglossal cyst is movement during:",o:["Jaw clenching","Shoulder shrugging","Neck extension","Eye closure","Tongue protrusion"],a:4,e:"Movement with tongue protrusion is the classical sign of thyroglossal cyst described in Dhingra. Midline swelling develops clinically commonly.<br><br>Persistent attachment to foramen cecum explains characteristic mobility during tongue movement.<br><br>Jaw clenching (option A), neck extension (option C), eye closure (option D), and shoulder shrugging (option B) are unrelated maneuvers.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest symptom of branchial cyst is:",o:["Painless neck swelling","Severe odynophagia","Inspiratory stridor","Recurrent epistaxis","Facial twitching"],a:0,e:"Painless lateral neck swelling is the commonest symptom of branchial cyst according to Dhingra. Infection develops clinically after upper respiratory illnesses.<br><br>The cyst enlarges gradually because of accumulation of epithelial secretions within cavity.<br><br>Severe odynophagia (option B), inspiratory stridor (option C), recurrent epistaxis (option D), and facial twitching (option E) are uncommon presentations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest complication after incomplete excision of branchial cyst is:",o:["Facial paralysis","Diplopia","Hearing loss","Horner syndrome","Recurrence"],a:4,e:"Recurrence is the commonest complication after incomplete branchial cyst excision according to Dhingra. Persistent discharge develops clinically in residual tracts.<br><br>Close relation of the tract to carotid vessels may complicate complete surgical removal.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), hearing loss (option C), Horner syndrome (option D), and diplopia (option B) are less common complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of thyroglossal cyst is at the level of:",o:["Thyroid cartilage","Hyoid bone","Cricoid cartilage","Angle of mandible","Suprasternal notch"],a:1,e:"Dhingra describes the hyoid level as the commonest site of thyroglossal cyst. Midline swelling develops clinically and moves with tongue protrusion.<br><br>The thyroglossal tract passes through or behind the central part of hyoid bone during embryological thyroid descent.<br><br>Thyroid cartilage (option A), cricoid cartilage (option C), angle of mandible (option D), and suprasternal notch (option E) are less common locations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest source of infection leading to Ludwig angina is:",o:["Tonsillitis","Otitis media","Nasopharyngitis","Lower molar tooth infection","Parotitis"],a:3,e:"Dhingra emphasizes lower molar dental infection as the commonest cause of Ludwig angina. Fever and toxic appearance develop clinically rapidly.<br><br>Roots of lower molars extend below mylohyoid attachment, allowing spread into submandibular spaces.<br><br>Tonsillitis (option A), otitis media (option B), nasopharyngitis (option C), and parotitis (option E) are less frequent causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous complication of deep neck space infection is:",o:["Facial palsy","Conductive deafness","Glossitis","Mediastinitis","Cataract formation"],a:3,e:"Mediastinitis is the most serious complication of deep neck infection according to Dhingra. Septic shock develops clinically with delayed treatment.<br><br>Infection spreads through the danger space extending from skull base into posterior mediastinum.<br><br>Facial palsy (option A), conductive deafness (option B), glossitis (option C), and cataract formation (option E) are less significant complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest congenital lateral neck cyst is:",o:["Thyroglossal cyst","Dermoid cyst","Ranula","Sebaceous cyst","Branchial cyst"],a:4,e:"Branchial cyst is described in Dhingra as the commonest congenital lateral neck cyst. Painless swelling develops clinically in young adults.<br><br>Most lesions arise from remnants of the second branchial cleft and cervical sinus.<br><br>Thyroglossal cyst (option A), dermoid cyst (option B), ranula (option C), and sebaceous cyst (option D) are less common lateral cysts.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The treatment of thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Aspiration only","Marsupialization","Sistrunk operation","Chemotherapy","Radiotherapy"],a:2,e:"Sistrunk operation is the standard treatment for thyroglossal cyst emphasized in Dhingra. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete excision.<br><br>The procedure includes removal of cyst, tract, and central part of hyoid bone.<br><br>Aspiration (option A), marsupialization (option B), chemotherapy (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inadequate treatments.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A laryngocele characteristically enlarges during:",o:["Swallowing","Tongue protrusion","Neck flexion","Jaw opening","Valsalva maneuver"],a:4,e:"Laryngocele classically enlarges during Valsalva maneuver according to Dhingra. Hoarseness develops clinically in internal lesions.<br><br>Raised intralaryngeal pressure forces air into the dilated laryngeal saccule.<br><br>Swallowing (option A), tongue protrusion (option B), neck flexion (option C), and jaw opening (option D) do not typically enlarge laryngoceles.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site of cystic hygroma is:",o:["Posterior triangle","Parotid region","Suprasternal notch","Midline neck","Submental region"],a:0,e:"Posterior triangle is the commonest site of cystic hygroma described in Dhingra. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>These congenital lymphatic malformations often infiltrate tissue planes diffusely.<br><br>Parotid region (option B), suprasternal notch (option C), midline neck (option D), and submental region (option E) are less common sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest symptom of branchial cyst is:",o:["Inspiratory stridor","Facial twitching","Recurrent epistaxis","Painless neck swelling","Diplopia"],a:3,e:"Painless lateral neck swelling is the classical presentation of branchial cyst according to Dhingra. Infection develops clinically after respiratory illnesses.<br><br>The cyst enlarges gradually because of accumulation of epithelial secretions.<br><br>Inspiratory stridor (option A), facial twitching (option B), recurrent epistaxis (option C), and diplopia (option E) are uncommon presentations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The danger space of neck extends from skull base to the:",o:["Clavicle","Carina","Thyroid cartilage","Sternum only","Posterior mediastinum"],a:4,e:"Dhingra emphasizes that the danger space extends into posterior mediastinum. Severe septic complications develop clinically if infection spreads downward.<br><br>Descending necrotizing mediastinitis may result from untreated deep neck infections.<br><br>Clavicle (option A), carina (option B), thyroid cartilage (option C), and sternum (option D) are incomplete limits.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest presentation of metastatic neck disease is:",o:["Ear discharge","Diplopia","Nasal obstruction","Facial paralysis","Neck swelling"],a:4,e:"Neck swelling is the commonest presentation of metastatic cervical disease according to Dhingra. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced malignancy.<br><br>Deep cervical nodes enlarge because of metastasis from upper aerodigestive tract cancers.<br><br>Ear discharge (option A), nasal obstruction (option C), facial paralysis (option D), and diplopia (option B) are less frequent presentations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest cause of congenital muscular torticollis is fibrosis of:",o:["Trapezius muscle","Digastric muscle","Platysma muscle","Omohyoid muscle","Sternocleidomastoid muscle"],a:4,e:"Fibrosis of sternocleidomastoid muscle is the characteristic lesion in congenital torticollis described in Dhingra. Facial asymmetry develops clinically in longstanding disease.<br><br>Birth trauma and ischemic injury are commonly implicated etiological factors.<br><br>Trapezius (option A), digastric (option B), platysma (option C), and omohyoid (option D) are less commonly involved.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest symptom of Ludwig angina is:",o:["Vertigo","Hearing loss","Facial pain","Dysphagia","Diplopia"],a:3,e:"Dysphagia is a frequent symptom of Ludwig angina according to Dhingra. Tongue elevation develops clinically because of floor-of-mouth cellulitis.<br><br>Diffuse infection in sublingual and submandibular spaces interferes with swallowing and airway patency.<br><br>Vertigo (option A), hearing loss (option B), facial pain (option C), and diplopia (option E) are unrelated symptoms.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The internal opening of a complete second branchial fistula lies in the:",o:["Pyriform fossa","Nasopharynx","Vallecula","Oral tongue","Tonsillar fossa"],a:4,e:"The internal opening of second branchial fistula lies near tonsillar fossa according to Dhingra. Mucoid discharge develops clinically from the external opening.<br><br>The tract passes between internal and external carotid arteries before reaching pharynx.<br><br>Pyriform fossa (option A), vallecula (option C), oral tongue (option D), and nasopharynx (option B) are less typical sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common organism causing deep neck infections is:",o:["Candida albicans","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Clostridium tetani","Streptococci"],a:4,e:"Streptococci are commonly isolated in deep neck infections according to Dhingra. Fever and severe odynophagia develop clinically prominently.<br><br>Mixed aerobic and anaerobic oral flora often participate in infection spread.<br><br>Candida (option A), tuberculosis (option B), Pseudomonas (option C), and Clostridium tetani (option D) are less common pathogens.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest source of cervical nodal metastasis is carcinoma of the:",o:["Orbit","External ear","Salivary duct","Thyroid cartilage","Upper aerodigestive tract"],a:4,e:"Upper aerodigestive tract carcinoma is the commonest source of cervical nodal metastasis according to Dhingra. Progressive neck swelling develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Rich lymphatic drainage facilitates early spread to deep cervical lymph nodes.<br><br>Orbit (option A), external ear (option B), thyroid cartilage (option D), and salivary duct (option C) are less common sources.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The external opening of branchial fistula is usually situated in the:",o:["Midline neck","Submental region","Mastoid region","Lower one-third of neck","Upper posterior triangle"],a:3,e:"The external opening of branchial fistula usually lies in lower one-third of neck according to Dhingra. Mucoid discharge develops clinically intermittently.<br><br>The opening is commonly situated near anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle.<br><br>Midline neck (option A), submental region (option B), mastoid region (option C), and upper posterior triangle (option E) are atypical sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest complication after incomplete excision of branchial cyst is:",o:["Facial paralysis","Horner syndrome","Hearing loss","Diplopia","Recurrence"],a:4,e:"Recurrence is the commonest complication after incomplete branchial cyst excision according to Dhingra. Persistent swelling develops clinically from residual epithelial tissue.<br><br>Close relation of the tract to carotid vessels may complicate complete removal.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), Horner syndrome (option B), hearing loss (option C), and diplopia (option D) are less frequent complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst classically moves with:",o:["Respiration only","Neck extension only","Swallowing and tongue protrusion","Jaw opening only","Eye closure only"],a:2,e:"Movement with swallowing and tongue protrusion is a classical feature of thyroglossal cyst emphasized in Dhingra. Midline swelling develops clinically prominently.<br><br>Persistent attachment to foramen cecum explains this characteristic mobility.<br><br>Respiration only (option A), neck extension (option B), jaw opening (option D), and eye closure (option E) are unrelated maneuvers.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred imaging investigation for cystic hygroma is:",o:["Plain X-ray neck","ECG","Sialography","MRI","Barium swallow"],a:3,e:"MRI is emphasized in Dhingra for assessing extent of cystic hygroma. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in extensive infiltrative lesions.<br><br>The investigation provides excellent soft tissue delineation and fascial plane definition.<br><br>Plain X-ray (option A), ECG (option B), sialography (option C), and barium swallow (option E) provide less anatomical detail.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous complication of Ludwig angina is:",o:["Facial paralysis","Diplopia","Cataract formation","Hearing loss","Airway obstruction"],a:4,e:"Airway obstruction is emphasized in Dhingra as the most serious complication of Ludwig angina. Tongue displacement develops clinically rapidly.<br><br>Diffuse cellulitis elevates and pushes tongue posteriorly, narrowing upper airway lumen.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), diplopia (option B), cataract formation (option C), and hearing loss (option D) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 52-year-old smoker presents with a painless upper deep cervical lymph node and no obvious oral lesion. The most likely occult primary site is:",o:["Upper aerodigestive tract","Orbit","Thyroid cartilage","External ear canal","Lacrimal gland"],a:0,e:"Cervical metastatic lymphadenopathy in adults should be considered metastatic squamous carcinoma until proven otherwise. Weight loss and dysphagia develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Upper aerodigestive tract malignancies commonly metastasize early through rich cervical lymphatic drainage.<br><br>Orbit (option B), thyroid cartilage (option C), external ear canal (option D), and lacrimal gland (option E) are less common primary sources.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with fever, torticollis, dysphagia, and bulging posterior pharyngeal wall. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Ludwig angina","Retropharyngeal abscess","Peritonsillar abscess","Mumps","Parotid abscess"],a:1,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess commonly occurs in children because retropharyngeal lymph nodes are prominent during early life. Respiratory distress develops clinically in severe disease.<br><br>Suppuration behind posterior pharyngeal wall produces dysphagia, neck stiffness, and torticollis.<br><br>Ludwig angina (option A), peritonsillar abscess (option C), mumps (option D), and parotid abscess (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"During Sistrunk operation, recurrence is prevented mainly by removing the:",o:["Entire thyroid gland","Strap muscles","Central part of hyoid bone","Sternocleidomastoid muscle","Thyroid cartilage"],a:2,e:"Removal of central hyoid bone is the key step of Sistrunk operation. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete tract excision.<br><br>The thyroglossal tract passes through or behind hyoid bone during embryological thyroid descent.<br><br>Entire thyroid gland (option A), strap muscles (option B), sternocleidomastoid muscle (option D), and thyroid cartilage (option E) are not routinely removed.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old man has a pulsatile neck swelling that is mobile horizontally but not vertically. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Lipoma","Sebaceous cyst","Carotid body tumor"],a:4,e:"Carotid body tumor classically shows Fontaine sign with side-to-side mobility but restricted vertical movement. Bruit develops clinically in vascular lesions.<br><br>The tumor arises at carotid bifurcation where vertical mobility becomes limited by attached vessels.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), sebaceous cyst (option D), and lipoma (option C) are nonvascular swellings.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common cause of cystic neck swelling in a young adult is:",o:["Metastatic lymph node","Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Dermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma"],a:2,e:"Branchial cyst commonly presents as a painless cystic neck swelling in young adults. Infection develops clinically after upper respiratory tract infections.<br><br>Most branchial cysts arise from remnants of the second branchial cleft.<br><br>Metastatic lymph node (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and cystic hygroma (option E) are less typical in this age group.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops shoulder drooping after radical neck dissection due to injury to the:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Lingual nerve","Spinal accessory nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],a:3,e:"Spinal accessory nerve injury produces trapezius paralysis with shoulder drooping and impaired arm abduction. Muscle wasting develops clinically progressively.<br><br>The nerve crosses posterior triangle superficially and remains vulnerable during neck dissection.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and glossopharyngeal nerve (option E) have different functions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Ludwig angina develops increasing stridor and restlessness. The immediate priority is:",o:["Start oral antibiotics only","Needle aspiration","Secure airway","Perform tonsillectomy","Give antihistamines"],a:2,e:"Airway obstruction is the most dangerous complication of Ludwig angina. Respiratory distress develops clinically because of tongue elevation and edema.<br><br>Airway management takes priority before definitive drainage and antibiotic therapy.<br><br>Oral antibiotics (option A), aspiration (option B), tonsillectomy (option D), and antihistamines (option E) are inadequate initial measures.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common congenital neck lesion presenting in infancy is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Thyroglossal cyst","Laryngocele","Lipoma"],a:1,e:"Cystic hygroma commonly presents in infancy as a soft transilluminant neck swelling. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>The lesion results from congenital malformation of lymphatic channels.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option C), laryngocele (option D), and lipoma (option E) are less common in infancy.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A lateral neck swelling in an elderly smoker should be considered malignant until proven otherwise because it is most likely:",o:["Dermoid cyst","Reactive node","Cystic hygroma","Sebaceous cyst","Metastatic lymphadenopathy"],a:4,e:"Metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy is the most important diagnosis in elderly smokers with lateral neck masses. Weight loss develops clinically frequently.<br><br>Squamous carcinoma from upper aerodigestive tract commonly spreads to cervical lymph nodes.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (option A), reactive node (option B), sebaceous cyst (option D), and cystic hygroma (option C) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for assessing extent of deep neck infection is:",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Tympanometry","ECG","Barium swallow","MRI or CT scan"],a:4,e:"CT and MRI are valuable for defining deep neck space infections and abscess formation. Airway compromise develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Cross-sectional imaging delineates fascial planes and mediastinal extension accurately.<br><br>Pure tone audiometry (option A), ECG (option C), barium swallow (option D), and tympanometry (option B) are less useful.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A branchial fistula usually passes between which arteries?",o:["Lingual and facial arteries","Common carotid and subclavian arteries","Internal and external carotid arteries","Vertebral and basilar arteries","Superior and inferior thyroid arteries"],a:2,e:"Second branchial fistulous tracts classically pass between internal and external carotid arteries. Recurrent discharge develops clinically intermittently.<br><br>This anatomical relation becomes important during surgical excision.<br><br>Lingual and facial arteries (option A), common carotid and subclavian arteries (option B), vertebral and basilar arteries (option D), and thyroid arteries (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with deep neck infection develops mediastinitis through spread via the:",o:["Pretracheal fascia only","Buccal space","Danger space","Carotid sheath only","Submandibular space only"],a:2,e:"The danger space extends from skull base to posterior mediastinum. Septic shock develops clinically if infection descends rapidly.<br><br>Deep neck infections may spread through this potential fascial plane into thoracic cavity.<br><br>Pretracheal fascia (option A), buccal space (option B), carotid sheath (option D), and submandibular space (option E) are less direct routes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of external opening of branchial fistula is:",o:["Midline neck","Near anterior border of sternocleidomastoid","Mastoid tip","Suprasternal notch","Submental region"],a:1,e:"Branchial fistula usually opens near anterior border of sternocleidomastoid in lower neck. Mucoid discharge develops clinically intermittently.<br><br>The anomaly commonly arises from persistence of second branchial cleft structures.<br><br>Midline neck (option A), mastoid tip (option C), suprasternal notch (option D), and submental region (option E) are atypical locations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A thyroglossal cyst fails to move on tongue protrusion when it is:",o:["Infected and fixed","Branchial in origin","Associated with laryngocele","Arising from parotid gland","Connected with thoracic duct"],a:0,e:"Thyroglossal cysts classically move with tongue protrusion, but movement may be restricted after repeated infection. Fibrosis develops clinically in chronic disease.<br><br>Inflammation causes adherence of the cyst to surrounding tissues.<br><br>Branchial origin (option B), laryngocele association (option C), parotid origin (option D), and thoracic duct connection (option E) are incorrect explanations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common primary malignancy metastasizing to cervical lymph nodes is:",o:["Adenocarcinoma","Lymphoma","Osteosarcoma","Melanoma","Squamous cell carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma is the commonest malignancy metastasizing to cervical lymph nodes. Tobacco exposure develops clinically as a major risk factor.<br><br>Most upper aerodigestive tract mucosa is lined by squamous epithelium.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma (option A), osteosarcoma (option C), melanoma (option D), and lymphoma (option B) are less common sources.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital torticollis most commonly presents with:",o:["Neck abscess","Hemoptysis","Facial nerve palsy","Inspiratory stridor","Head tilt to one side"],a:4,e:"Congenital muscular torticollis typically presents with head tilt toward affected side. Facial asymmetry develops clinically in longstanding cases.<br><br>Fibrosis of sternocleidomastoid muscle limits normal neck movement.<br><br>Neck abscess (option A), facial palsy (option C), inspiratory stridor (option D), and hemoptysis (option B) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest symptom of laryngocele is:",o:["Epistaxis","Hoarseness","Otorrhea","Diplopia","Trismus"],a:1,e:"Hoarseness is the commonest symptom of laryngocele described in Dhingra. Neck swelling develops clinically in external lesions.<br><br>Internal laryngoceles interfere with supraglottic airway and phonation.<br><br>Epistaxis (option A), otorrhea (option C), diplopia (option D), and trismus (option E) are unrelated symptoms.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A brilliantly transilluminant swelling in posterior triangle of infant is most likely:",o:["Lipoma","Branchial cyst","Cystic hygroma","Thyroglossal cyst","Sebaceous cyst"],a:2,e:"Cystic hygroma commonly presents as a transilluminant multiloculated swelling in posterior triangle. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in extensive lesions.<br><br>The lesion arises from congenital malformation of lymphatic channels.<br><br>Lipoma (option A), branchial cyst (option B), thyroglossal cyst (option D), and sebaceous cyst (option E) are less transilluminant.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation of choice for a suspected metastatic cervical node is:",o:["FNAC","Pure tone audiometry","Barium swallow","Tympanometry","Rhinomanometry"],a:0,e:"FNAC is the investigation of choice for evaluating cervical lymphadenopathy. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced metastatic disease.<br><br>The procedure is minimally invasive and provides rapid cytological diagnosis.<br><br>Pure tone audiometry (option B), barium swallow (option C), tympanometry (option D), and rhinomanometry (option E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous complication of retropharyngeal abscess is:",o:["Facial paralysis","Trigeminal neuralgia","Hearing loss","Cataract formation","Airway obstruction"],a:4,e:"Airway obstruction is the most dangerous complication of retropharyngeal abscess. Respiratory distress develops clinically because of posterior pharyngeal wall bulging.<br><br>Edema and abscess expansion narrow upper airway rapidly in children.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), hearing loss (option C), cataract formation (option D), and trigeminal neuralgia (option B) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old chronic smoker presents with a painless left level II cervical node measuring 3 cm. Oral cavity examination is normal, but indirect laryngoscopy reveals pooling of saliva in pyriform fossa. The most likely primary site is:",o:["Nasopharynx","Base of tongue","Supraglottis","Hypopharynx","Thyroid gland"],a:3,e:"Hypopharyngeal carcinoma commonly presents with metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy before obvious throat symptoms appear. Dysphagia and referred otalgia develop clinically later in disease progression.<br><br>Pooling of saliva in pyriform fossa is an important indirect laryngoscopic clue suggesting hypopharyngeal growth obstructing normal pharyngeal clearance.<br><br>Nasopharynx (option A), base of tongue (option B), supraglottis (option C), and thyroid gland (option E) are less consistent with this presentation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most appropriate investigation for initial evaluation of a metastatic cervical lymph node is:",o:["Excision biopsy","MRI neck","Open lymph node biopsy","PET scan","FNAC"],a:4,e:"FNAC is considered the first-line investigation for metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy. Weight loss and progressive nodal enlargement develop clinically in advanced malignancy.<br><br>The technique is minimally invasive, rapid, and avoids tumor seeding associated with unnecessary open biopsy procedures.<br><br>Excision biopsy (option A), MRI (option B), open biopsy (option C), and PET scan (option D) are not preferred initial tests.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 7-year-old child develops fever, neck stiffness, muffled voice, and torticollis after an upper respiratory tract infection. Lateral neck radiograph shows widening of prevertebral soft tissue. The diagnosis is:",o:["Ludwig angina","Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Acute epiglottitis","Branchial cyst infection"],a:2,e:"Retropharyngeal abscess is common in children because retropharyngeal lymph nodes remain prominent during early childhood. Airway compromise develops clinically in severe disease.<br><br>Prevertebral soft tissue widening on lateral neck X-ray strongly supports pus collection within retropharyngeal space.<br><br>Ludwig angina (option A), peritonsillar abscess (option B), acute epiglottitis (option D), and branchial cyst infection (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"During surgical excision of a second branchial fistula, the tract classically passes between the:",o:["Lingual and facial arteries","Internal and external carotid arteries","Vertebral and basilar arteries","Superior and inferior thyroid arteries","Maxillary and superficial temporal arteries"],a:1,e:"Second branchial fistulous tracts characteristically pass between internal and external carotid arteries. Recurrent mucoid discharge develops clinically from the external opening.<br><br>Knowledge of this anatomical relationship is essential during surgery to avoid major vascular injury.<br><br>Lingual and facial arteries (option A), vertebral and basilar arteries (option C), thyroid arteries (option D), and terminal external carotid branches (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 42-year-old man presents with pulsatile swelling at carotid bifurcation. The mass is mobile horizontally but not vertically and produces bruit on auscultation. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Laryngocele","Lipoma","Carotid body tumor"],a:4,e:"Carotid body tumor classically demonstrates Fontaine sign with side-to-side mobility but restricted vertical movement. Cranial nerve palsies develop clinically in advanced lesions.<br><br>The tumor arises from paraganglionic tissue at carotid bifurcation and remains closely attached to major vessels.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), laryngocele (option C), and lipoma (option D) are nonvascular masses.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The definitive treatment of thyroglossal cyst is:",o:["Simple aspiration","Marsupialization","Antibiotics alone","Sistrunk operation","Incision and drainage"],a:3,e:"Sistrunk operation is the standard definitive treatment for thyroglossal cyst. Recurrence develops clinically after incomplete tract excision.<br><br>The procedure includes removal of cyst, tract, and central portion of hyoid bone to eliminate residual embryological tissue.<br><br>Aspiration (option A), marsupialization (option B), antibiotics (option C), and incision with drainage (option E) are inadequate definitive measures.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 4-year-old infant presents with a soft transilluminant swelling occupying posterior triangle and extending into axilla. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Hemangioma","Lipoma","Thyroglossal cyst","Cystic hygroma"],a:4,e:"Cystic hygroma commonly presents as a multiloculated transilluminant lesion in posterior triangle during infancy. Respiratory distress develops clinically in extensive disease.<br><br>The lesion results from congenital malformation of lymphatic channels with infiltration across fascial planes.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), hemangioma (option B), lipoma (option C), and thyroglossal cyst (option D) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous complication of Ludwig angina is:",o:["Facial paralysis","Meningitis","Hearing loss","Airway obstruction","Cavernous sinus thrombosis"],a:3,e:"Airway obstruction is the most serious complication of Ludwig angina. Respiratory distress develops clinically because of tongue elevation and floor-of-mouth edema.<br><br>Rapid spread of cellulitis within submandibular and sublingual spaces narrows the upper airway significantly.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), meningitis (option B), hearing loss (option C), and cavernous sinus thrombosis (option E) are less immediate dangers.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 63-year-old smoker presents with a hard fixed cervical lymph node. Panendoscopy fails to reveal primary lesion. Which investigation best helps detect occult primary tumor?",o:["Ultrasonography","FNAC only","Plain neck radiograph","Barium swallow","PET-CT scan"],a:4,e:"PET-CT is highly useful in identifying occult primary tumors in patients presenting with metastatic cervical lymphadenopathy. Weight loss develops clinically in advanced malignancy.<br><br>The investigation detects metabolically active lesions that may remain hidden on routine endoscopy and imaging.<br><br>Ultrasonography (option A), FNAC alone (option B), plain radiograph (option C), and barium swallow (option D) are less sensitive.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops shoulder drooping and inability to abduct arm above shoulder level after radical neck dissection. The injured nerve is:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Lingual nerve","Phrenic nerve","Spinal accessory nerve"],a:4,e:"Spinal accessory nerve injury produces trapezius paralysis with shoulder drooping and impaired abduction above horizontal level. Muscle wasting develops clinically progressively.<br><br>The nerve crosses posterior triangle superficially and is vulnerable during radical neck dissection procedures.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option B), lingual nerve (option C), and phrenic nerve (option D) serve different functions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
];